69 /* The pool allocator block. Redis Modules can allocate memory via this special
70  * allocator that will automatically release it all once the callback returns.
71  * This means that it can only be used for ephemeral allocations. However
72  * there are two advantages for modules to use this API:
73  *
74  * 1) The memory is automatically released when the callback returns.
75  * 2) This allocator is faster for many small allocations since whole blocks
76  * are allocated, and small pieces returned to the caller just advancing
77  * the index of the allocation.
78  *
79  * Allocations are always rounded to the size of the void pointer in order
80  * to always return aligned memory chunks. */
81 
82 #define REDISMODULE_POOL_ALLOC_MIN_SIZE (1024*8)
83 #define REDISMODULE_POOL_ALLOC_ALIGN (sizeof(void*))
84

90 } RedisModulePoolAllocBlock;

311 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
312  * Pool allocator
313  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

315 /* Release the chain of blocks used for pool allocations. */
316 void poolAllocRelease(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
317  RedisModulePoolAllocBlock *head = ctx->pa_head, *next;
318 
319  while(head != NULL) {
320  next = head->next;
321  zfree(head);
322  head = next;
323  }
324  ctx->pa_head = NULL;
325 }
326 
327 /* Return heap allocated memory that will be freed automatically when the
328  * module callback function returns. Mostly suitable for small allocations
329  * that are short living and must be released when the callback returns
330  * anyway. The returned memory is aligned to the architecture word size
331  * if at least word size bytes are requested, otherwise it is just
332  * aligned to the next power of two, so for example a 3 bytes request is
333  * 4 bytes aligned while a 2 bytes request is 2 bytes aligned.
334  *
335  * There is no realloc style function since when this is needed to use the
336  * pool allocator is not a good idea.
337  *
338  * The function returns NULL if `bytes` is 0. */
339 void *RM_PoolAlloc(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, size_t bytes) {
340  if (bytes == 0) return NULL;
341  RedisModulePoolAllocBlock *b = ctx->pa_head;
342  size_t left = b ? b->size - b->used : 0;
343 
344  /* Fix alignment. */
345  if (left >= bytes) {
346  size_t alignment = REDISMODULE_POOL_ALLOC_ALIGN;
347  while (bytes < alignment && alignment/2 >= bytes) alignment /= 2;
348  if (b->used % alignment)
349  b->used += alignment - (b->used % alignment);
350  left = (b->used > b->size) ? 0 : b->size - b->used;
351  }
352 
353  /* Create a new block if needed. */
354  if (left < bytes) {
355  size_t blocksize = REDISMODULE_POOL_ALLOC_MIN_SIZE;
356  if (blocksize < bytes) blocksize = bytes;
357  b = zmalloc(sizeof(*b) + blocksize);
358  b->size = blocksize;
359  b->used = 0;
360  b->next = ctx->pa_head;
361  ctx->pa_head = b;
362  }
363 
364  char *retval = b->memory + b->used;
365  b->used += bytes;
366  return retval;
367 }

373 /* Create an empty key of the specified type. 'kp' must point to a key object
374  * opened for writing where the .value member is set to NULL because the
375  * key was found to be non existing.
376  *
377  * On success REDISMODULE_OK is returned and the key is populated with
378  * the value of the specified type. The function fails and returns
379  * REDISMODULE_ERR if:
380  *
381  * 1) The key is not open for writing.
382  * 2) The key is not empty.
383  * 3) The specified type is unknown.
384  */
385 int moduleCreateEmptyKey(RedisModuleKey *key, int type) {
386  robj *obj;
387 
388  /* The key must be open for writing and non existing to proceed. */
389  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE) || key->value)
390  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
391 
392  switch(type) {
393  case REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_LIST:
394  obj = createQuicklistObject();
395  quicklistSetOptions(obj->ptr, server.list_max_ziplist_size,
396  server.list_compress_depth);
397  break;
398  case REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_ZSET:
399  obj = createZsetZiplistObject();
400  break;
401  case REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_HASH:
402  obj = createHashObject();
403  break;
404  default: return REDISMODULE_ERR;
405  }
406  dbAdd(key->db,key->key,obj);
407  key->value = obj;
408  return REDISMODULE_OK;
409 }
410 
411 /* This function is called in low-level API implementation functions in order
412  * to check if the value associated with the key remained empty after an
413  * operation that removed elements from an aggregate data type.
414  *
415  * If this happens, the key is deleted from the DB and the key object state
416  * is set to the right one in order to be targeted again by write operations
417  * possibly recreating the key if needed.
418  *
419  * The function returns 1 if the key value object is found empty and is
420  * deleted, otherwise 0 is returned. */
421 int moduleDelKeyIfEmpty(RedisModuleKey *key) {
422  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE) || key->value == NULL) return 0;
423  int isempty;
424  robj *o = key->value;
425 
426  switch(o->type) {
427  case OBJ_LIST: isempty = listTypeLength(o) == 0; break;
428  case OBJ_SET: isempty = setTypeSize(o) == 0; break;
429  case OBJ_ZSET: isempty = zsetLength(o) == 0; break;
430  case OBJ_HASH : isempty = hashTypeLength(o) == 0; break;
431  default: isempty = 0;
432  }
433 
434  if (isempty) {
435  dbDelete(key->db,key->key);
436  key->value = NULL;
437  return 1;
438  } else {
439  return 0;
440  }
441 }

453 /* Lookup the requested module API and store the function pointer into the
454  * target pointer. The function returns REDISMODULE_ERR if there is no such
455  * named API, otherwise REDISMODULE_OK.
456  *
457  * This function is not meant to be used by modules developer, it is only

466 /* Free the context after the user function was called. */
467 void moduleFreeContext(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
468  autoMemoryCollect(ctx);
469  poolAllocRelease(ctx);
470  if (ctx->postponed_arrays) {
471  zfree(ctx->postponed_arrays);
472  ctx->postponed_arrays_count = 0;
473  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
474  "API misuse detected in module %s: "
475  "RedisModule_ReplyWithArray(REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN) "
476  "not matched by the same number of RedisModule_SetReplyArrayLen() "
477  "calls.",
478  ctx->module->name);
479  }
480  if (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_THREAD_SAFE) freeClient(ctx->client);
481 }

483 /* Helper function for when a command callback is called, in order to handle
484  * details needed to correctly replicate commands. */
485 void moduleHandlePropagationAfterCommandCallback(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
486  client *c = ctx->client;
487 
488  if (c->flags & CLIENT_LUA) return;
489 
490  /* Handle the replication of the final EXEC, since whatever a command
491  * emits is always wrapped around MULTI/EXEC. */
492  if (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_MULTI_EMITTED) {
493  robj *propargv[1];
494  propargv[0] = createStringObject("EXEC",4);
495  alsoPropagate(server.execCommand,c->db->id,propargv,1,
496  PROPAGATE_AOF|PROPAGATE_REPL);
497  decrRefCount(propargv[0]);
498  }
499 }

501 /* This Redis command binds the normal Redis command invocation with commands
502  * exported by modules. */
503 void RedisModuleCommandDispatcher(client *c) {
504  RedisModuleCommandProxy *cp = (void*)(unsigned long)c->cmd->getkeys_proc;
505  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
506 
507  ctx.module = cp->module;
508  ctx.client = c;
509  cp->func(&ctx,(void**)c->argv,c->argc);
510  moduleHandlePropagationAfterCommandCallback(&ctx);
511  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);

514 /* This function returns the list of keys, with the same interface as the
515  * 'getkeys' function of the native commands, for module commands that exported
516  * the "getkeys-api" flag during the registration. This is done when the
517  * list of keys are not at fixed positions, so that first/last/step cannot
518  * be used.
519  *
520  * In order to accomplish its work, the module command is called, flagging
521  * the context in a way that the command can recognize this is a special
522  * "get keys" call by calling RedisModule_IsKeysPositionRequest(ctx). */
523 int *moduleGetCommandKeysViaAPI(struct redisCommand *cmd, robj **argv, int argc, int *numkeys) {
524  RedisModuleCommandProxy *cp = (void*)(unsigned long)cmd->getkeys_proc;
525  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
526 
527  ctx.module = cp->module;
528  ctx.client = NULL;
529  ctx.flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_KEYS_POS_REQUEST;
530  cp->func(&ctx,(void**)argv,argc);
531  int *res = ctx.keys_pos;
532  if (numkeys) *numkeys = ctx.keys_count;
533  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
534  return res;
535 }

537 /* Return non-zero if a module command, that was declared with the
538  * flag "getkeys-api", is called in a special way to get the keys positions
539  * and not to get executed. Otherwise zero is returned. */
540 int RM_IsKeysPositionRequest(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
541  return (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_KEYS_POS_REQUEST) != 0;
542 }

544 /* When a module command is called in order to obtain the position of
545  * keys, since it was flagged as "getkeys-api" during the registration,
546  * the command implementation checks for this special call using the
547  * RedisModule_IsKeysPositionRequest() API and uses this function in
548  * order to report keys, like in the following example:
549  *
550  * if (RedisModule_IsKeysPositionRequest(ctx)) {
551  * RedisModule_KeyAtPos(ctx,1);
552  * RedisModule_KeyAtPos(ctx,2);
553  * }
554  *
555  * Note: in the example below the get keys API would not be needed since
556  * keys are at fixed positions. This interface is only used for commands
557  * with a more complex structure. */
558 void RM_KeyAtPos(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, int pos) {
559  if (!(ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_KEYS_POS_REQUEST)) return;
560  if (pos <= 0) return;
561  ctx->keys_pos = zrealloc(ctx->keys_pos,sizeof(int)*(ctx->keys_count+1));
562  ctx->keys_pos[ctx->keys_count++] = pos;
563 }

565 /* Helper for RM_CreateCommand(). Turns a string representing command
566  * flags into the command flags used by the Redis core.
567  *
568  * It returns the set of flags, or -1 if unknown flags are found. */
569 int commandFlagsFromString(char *s) {
570  int count, j;
571  int flags = 0;
572  sds *tokens = sdssplitlen(s,strlen(s)," ",1,&count);
573  for (j = 0; j < count; j++) {
574  char *t = tokens[j];
575  if (!strcasecmp(t,"write")) flags |= CMD_WRITE;
576  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"readonly")) flags |= CMD_READONLY;
577  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"admin")) flags |= CMD_ADMIN;
578  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"deny-oom")) flags |= CMD_DENYOOM;
579  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"deny-script")) flags |= CMD_NOSCRIPT;
580  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"allow-loading")) flags |= CMD_LOADING;
581  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"pubsub")) flags |= CMD_PUBSUB;
582  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"random")) flags |= CMD_RANDOM;
583  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"allow-stale")) flags |= CMD_STALE;
584  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"no-monitor")) flags |= CMD_SKIP_MONITOR;
585  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"fast")) flags |= CMD_FAST;
586  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"getkeys-api")) flags |= CMD_MODULE_GETKEYS;
587  else if (!strcasecmp(t,"no-cluster")) flags |= CMD_MODULE_NO_CLUSTER;
588  else break;
589  }
590  sdsfreesplitres(tokens,count);
591  if (j != count) return -1; /* Some token not processed correctly. */
592  return flags;
593 }
594 
595 /* Register a new command in the Redis server, that will be handled by
596  * calling the function pointer 'func' using the RedisModule calling
597  * convention. The function returns REDISMODULE_ERR if the specified command
598  * name is already busy or a set of invalid flags were passed, otherwise
599  * REDISMODULE_OK is returned and the new command is registered.
600  *
601  * This function must be called during the initialization of the module
602  * inside the RedisModule_OnLoad() function. Calling this function outside
603  * of the initialization function is not defined.
604  *
605  * The command function type is the following:
606  *
607  * int MyCommand_RedisCommand(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString **argv, int argc);
608  *
609  * And is supposed to always return REDISMODULE_OK.
610  *
611  * The set of flags 'strflags' specify the behavior of the command, and should
612  * be passed as a C string composed of space separated words, like for
613  * example "write deny-oom". The set of flags are:
614  *
615  * * **"write"**: The command may modify the data set (it may also read
616  * from it).
617  * * **"readonly"**: The command returns data from keys but never writes.
618  * * **"admin"**: The command is an administrative command (may change
619  * replication or perform similar tasks).
620  * * **"deny-oom"**: The command may use additional memory and should be
621  * denied during out of memory conditions.
622  * * **"deny-script"**: Don't allow this command in Lua scripts.
623  * * **"allow-loading"**: Allow this command while the server is loading data.
624  * Only commands not interacting with the data set
625  * should be allowed to run in this mode. If not sure
626  * don't use this flag.
627  * * **"pubsub"**: The command publishes things on Pub/Sub channels.
628  * * **"random"**: The command may have different outputs even starting
629  * from the same input arguments and key values.
630  * * **"allow-stale"**: The command is allowed to run on slaves that don't
631  * serve stale data. Don't use if you don't know what
632  * this means.
633  * * **"no-monitor"**: Don't propagate the command on monitor. Use this if
634  * the command has sensible data among the arguments.
635  * * **"fast"**: The command time complexity is not greater
636  * than O(log(N)) where N is the size of the collection or
637  * anything else representing the normal scalability
638  * issue with the command.
639  * * **"getkeys-api"**: The command implements the interface to return
640  * the arguments that are keys. Used when start/stop/step
641  * is not enough because of the command syntax.
642  * * **"no-cluster"**: The command should not register in Redis Cluster
643  * since is not designed to work with it because, for
644  * example, is unable to report the position of the
645  * keys, programmatically creates key names, or any
646  * other reason.
647  */
648 int RM_CreateCommand(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *name, RedisModuleCmdFunc cmdfunc, const char *strflags, int firstkey, int lastkey, int keystep) {
649  int flags = strflags ? commandFlagsFromString((char*)strflags) : 0;
650  if (flags == -1) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
651  if ((flags & CMD_MODULE_NO_CLUSTER) && server.cluster_enabled)
652  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
653 
654  struct redisCommand *rediscmd;
655  RedisModuleCommandProxy *cp;
656  sds cmdname = sdsnew(name);
657 
658  /* Check if the command name is busy. */
659  if (lookupCommand(cmdname) != NULL) {
660  sdsfree(cmdname);
661  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
662  }
663 
664  /* Create a command "proxy", which is a structure that is referenced
665  * in the command table, so that the generic command that works as
666  * binding between modules and Redis, can know what function to call
667  * and what the module is.
668  *
669  * Note that we use the Redis command table 'getkeys_proc' in order to
670  * pass a reference to the command proxy structure. */
671  cp = zmalloc(sizeof(*cp));
672  cp->module = ctx->module;
673  cp->func = cmdfunc;
674  cp->rediscmd = zmalloc(sizeof(*rediscmd));
675  cp->rediscmd->name = cmdname;
676  cp->rediscmd->proc = RedisModuleCommandDispatcher;
677  cp->rediscmd->arity = -1;
678  cp->rediscmd->flags = flags | CMD_MODULE;
679  cp->rediscmd->getkeys_proc = (redisGetKeysProc*)(unsigned long)cp;
680  cp->rediscmd->firstkey = firstkey;
681  cp->rediscmd->lastkey = lastkey;
682  cp->rediscmd->keystep = keystep;
683  cp->rediscmd->microseconds = 0;
684  cp->rediscmd->calls = 0;
685  dictAdd(server.commands,sdsdup(cmdname),cp->rediscmd);
686  dictAdd(server.orig_commands,sdsdup(cmdname),cp->rediscmd);
687  return REDISMODULE_OK;
688 }

732 /* Add a new object to release automatically when the callback returns. */
733 void autoMemoryAdd(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, int type, void *ptr) {
734  if (!(ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_AUTO_MEMORY)) return;
735  if (ctx->amqueue_used == ctx->amqueue_len) {
736  ctx->amqueue_len *= 2;
737  if (ctx->amqueue_len < 16) ctx->amqueue_len = 16;
738  ctx->amqueue = zrealloc(ctx->amqueue,sizeof(struct AutoMemEntry)*ctx->amqueue_len);
739  }
740  ctx->amqueue[ctx->amqueue_used].type = type;
741  ctx->amqueue[ctx->amqueue_used].ptr = ptr;
742  ctx->amqueue_used++;
743 }
744 
745 /* Mark an object as freed in the auto release queue, so that users can still
746  * free things manually if they want.
747  *
748  * The function returns 1 if the object was actually found in the auto memory
749  * pool, otherwise 0 is returned. */
750 int autoMemoryFreed(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, int type, void *ptr) {
751  if (!(ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_AUTO_MEMORY)) return 0;
752 
753  int count = (ctx->amqueue_used+1)/2;
754  for (int j = 0; j < count; j++) {
755  for (int side = 0; side < 2; side++) {
756  /* For side = 0 check right side of the array, for
757  * side = 1 check the left side instead (zig-zag scanning). */
758  int i = (side == 0) ? (ctx->amqueue_used - 1 - j) : j;
759  if (ctx->amqueue[i].type == type &&
760  ctx->amqueue[i].ptr == ptr)
761  {
762  ctx->amqueue[i].type = REDISMODULE_AM_FREED;
763 
764  /* Switch the freed element and the last element, to avoid growing
765  * the queue unnecessarily if we allocate/free in a loop */
766  if (i != ctx->amqueue_used-1) {
767  ctx->amqueue[i] = ctx->amqueue[ctx->amqueue_used-1];
768  }
769 
770  /* Reduce the size of the queue because we either moved the top
771  * element elsewhere or freed it */
772  ctx->amqueue_used--;
773  return 1;
774  }
775  }
776  }
777  return 0;
778 }
779 
780 /* Release all the objects in queue. */
781 void autoMemoryCollect(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
782  if (!(ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_AUTO_MEMORY)) return;
783  /* Clear the AUTO_MEMORY flag from the context, otherwise the functions
784  * we call to free the resources, will try to scan the auto release
785  * queue to mark the entries as freed. */
786  ctx->flags &= ~REDISMODULE_CTX_AUTO_MEMORY;
787  int j;
788  for (j = 0; j < ctx->amqueue_used; j++) {
789  void *ptr = ctx->amqueue[j].ptr;
790  switch(ctx->amqueue[j].type) {
791  case REDISMODULE_AM_STRING: decrRefCount(ptr); break;
792  case REDISMODULE_AM_REPLY: RM_FreeCallReply(ptr); break;
793  case REDISMODULE_AM_KEY: RM_CloseKey(ptr); break;
794  case REDISMODULE_AM_DICT: RM_FreeDict(NULL,ptr); break;
795  }
796  }
797  ctx->flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_AUTO_MEMORY;
798  zfree(ctx->amqueue);
799  ctx->amqueue = NULL;
800  ctx->amqueue_len = 0;
801  ctx->amqueue_used = 0;
802 }

808 /* Create a new module string object. The returned string must be freed
809  * with RedisModule_FreeString(), unless automatic memory is enabled.
810  *
811  * The string is created by copying the `len` bytes starting
812  * at `ptr`. No reference is retained to the passed buffer.
813  *
814  * The module context 'ctx' is optional and may be NULL if you want to create
815  * a string out of the context scope. However in that case, the automatic
816  * memory management will not be available, and the string memory must be
817  * managed manually. */

819  RedisModuleString *o = createStringObject(ptr,len);

821  return o;

824 /* Create a new module string object from a printf format and arguments.
825  * The returned string must be freed with RedisModule_FreeString(), unless
826  * automatic memory is enabled.
827  *
828  * The string is created using the sds formatter function sdscatvprintf().
829  *
830  * The passed context 'ctx' may be NULL if necessary, see the
831  * RedisModule_CreateString() documentation for more info. */
832 RedisModuleString *RM_CreateStringPrintf(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *fmt, ...) {
833  sds s = sdsempty();
834 
835  va_list ap;
836  va_start(ap, fmt);
837  s = sdscatvprintf(s, fmt, ap);
838  va_end(ap);
839 
840  RedisModuleString *o = createObject(OBJ_STRING, s);
841  if (ctx != NULL) autoMemoryAdd(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_STRING,o);
842 
843  return o;
844 }

875 /* Free a module string object obtained with one of the Redis modules API calls
876  * that return new string objects.
877  *
878  * It is possible to call this function even when automatic memory management
879  * is enabled. In that case the string will be released ASAP and removed
880  * from the pool of string to release at the end.
881  *
882  * If the string was created with a NULL context 'ctx', it is also possible to
883  * pass ctx as NULL when releasing the string (but passing a context will not
884  * create any issue). Strings created with a context should be freed also passing
885  * the context, so if you want to free a string out of context later, make sure
886  * to create it using a NULL context. */
887 void RM_FreeString(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString *str) {
888  decrRefCount(str);
889  if (ctx != NULL) autoMemoryFreed(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_STRING,str);
890 }
891 
892 /* Every call to this function, will make the string 'str' requiring
893  * an additional call to RedisModule_FreeString() in order to really
894  * free the string. Note that the automatic freeing of the string obtained
895  * enabling modules automatic memory management counts for one
896  * RedisModule_FreeString() call (it is just executed automatically).
897  *
898  * Normally you want to call this function when, at the same time
899  * the following conditions are true:
900  *
901  * 1) You have automatic memory management enabled.
902  * 2) You want to create string objects.
903  * 3) Those string objects you create need to live *after* the callback
904  * function(for example a command implementation) creating them returns.
905  *
906  * Usually you want this in order to store the created string object
907  * into your own data structure, for example when implementing a new data
908  * type.
909  *
910  * Note that when memory management is turned off, you don't need
911  * any call to RetainString() since creating a string will always result
912  * into a string that lives after the callback function returns, if
913  * no FreeString() call is performed.
914  *
915  * It is possible to call this function with a NULL context. */
916 void RM_RetainString(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString *str) {
917  if (ctx == NULL || !autoMemoryFreed(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_STRING,str)) {
918  /* Increment the string reference counting only if we can't
919  * just remove the object from the list of objects that should
920  * be reclaimed. Why we do that, instead of just incrementing
921  * the refcount in any case, and let the automatic FreeString()
922  * call at the end to bring the refcount back at the desired
923  * value? Because this way we ensure that the object refcount
924  * value is 1 (instead of going to 2 to be dropped later to 1)
925  * after the call to this function. This is needed for functions
926  * like RedisModule_StringAppendBuffer() to work. */
927  incrRefCount(str);
928  }
929 }

931 /* Given a string module object, this function returns the string pointer
932  * and length of the string. The returned pointer and length should only
933  * be used for read only accesses and never modified. */
934 const char *RM_StringPtrLen(const RedisModuleString *str, size_t *len) {
935  if (str == NULL) {
936  const char *errmsg = "(NULL string reply referenced in module)";
937  if (len) *len = strlen(errmsg);
938  return errmsg;
939  }
940  if (len) *len = sdslen(str->ptr);
941  return str->ptr;
942 }

972 /* Return the (possibly modified in encoding) input 'str' object if
973  * the string is unshared, otherwise NULL is returned. */
974 RedisModuleString *moduleAssertUnsharedString(RedisModuleString *str) {
975  if (str->refcount != 1) {
976  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
977  "Module attempted to use an in-place string modify operation "
978  "with a string referenced multiple times. Please check the code "
979  "for API usage correctness.");
980  return NULL;
981  }
982  if (str->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_EMBSTR) {
983  /* Note: here we "leak" the additional allocation that was
984  * used in order to store the embedded string in the object. */
985  str->ptr = sdsnewlen(str->ptr,sdslen(str->ptr));
986  str->encoding = OBJ_ENCODING_RAW;
987  } else if (str->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_INT) {
988  /* Convert the string from integer to raw encoding. */
989  str->ptr = sdsfromlonglong((long)str->ptr);
990  str->encoding = OBJ_ENCODING_RAW;
991  }
992  return str;
993 }

995 /* Append the specified buffer to the string 'str'. The string must be a
996  * string created by the user that is referenced only a single time, otherwise
997  * REDISMODULE_ERR is returned and the operation is not performed. */
998 int RM_StringAppendBuffer(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleString *str, const char *buf, size_t len) {
999  UNUSED(ctx);
1000  str = moduleAssertUnsharedString(str);
1001  if (str == NULL) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1002  str->ptr = sdscatlen(str->ptr,buf,len);
1003  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1004 }

1016 /* Send an error about the number of arguments given to the command,
1017  * citing the command name in the error message.

1030 /* Return the client object the `RM_Reply*` functions should target.
1031  * Normally this is just `ctx->client`, that is the client that called
1032  * the module command, however in the case of thread safe contexts there
1033  * is no directly associated client (since it would not be safe to access
1034  * the client from a thread), so instead the blocked client object referenced
1035  * in the thread safe context, has a fake client that we just use to accumulate
1036  * the replies. Later, when the client is unblocked, the accumulated replies
1037  * are appended to the actual client.
1038  *
1039  * The function returns the client pointer depending on the context, or
1040  * NULL if there is no potential client. This happens when we are in the
1041  * context of a thread safe context that was not initialized with a blocked
1042  * client object. Other contexts without associated clients are the ones
1043  * initialized to run the timers callbacks. */
1044 client *moduleGetReplyClient(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
1045  if (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_THREAD_SAFE) {
1046  if (ctx->blocked_client)
1047  return ctx->blocked_client->reply_client;
1048  else
1049  return NULL;
1050  } else {
1051  /* If this is a non thread safe context, just return the client
1052  * that is running the command if any. This may be NULL as well
1053  * in the case of contexts that are not executed with associated
1054  * clients, like timer contexts. */
1055  return ctx->client;
1056  }
1057 }

1068 /* Reply with an error or simple string (status message). Used to implement
1069  * ReplyWithSimpleString() and ReplyWithError().
1070  * The function always returns REDISMODULE_OK. */
1071 int replyWithStatus(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *msg, char *prefix) {
1072  client *c = moduleGetReplyClient(ctx);
1073  if (c == NULL) return REDISMODULE_OK;

1075  strmsg = sdscat(strmsg,msg);
1076  strmsg = sdscatlen(strmsg,"\r\n",2);
1077  addReplySds(c,strmsg);
1078  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1079 }

1108 /* Reply with an array type of 'len' elements. However 'len' other calls
1109  * to `ReplyWith*` style functions must follow in order to emit the elements
1110  * of the array.
1111  *
1112  * When producing arrays with a number of element that is not known beforehand
1113  * the function can be called with the special count
1114  * REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN, and the actual number of elements can be
1115  * later set with RedisModule_ReplySetArrayLength() (which will set the
1116  * latest "open" count if there are multiple ones).
1117  *
1118  * The function always returns REDISMODULE_OK. */
1119 int RM_ReplyWithArray(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, long len) {
1120  client *c = moduleGetReplyClient(ctx);
1121  if (c == NULL) return REDISMODULE_OK;
1122  if (len == REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN) {
1123  ctx->postponed_arrays = zrealloc(ctx->postponed_arrays,sizeof(void*)*
1124  (ctx->postponed_arrays_count+1));
1125  ctx->postponed_arrays[ctx->postponed_arrays_count] =
1126  addDeferredMultiBulkLength(c);
1127  ctx->postponed_arrays_count++;
1128  } else {
1129  addReplyMultiBulkLen(c,len);
1130  }
1131  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1132 }
1133 
1134 /* When RedisModule_ReplyWithArray() is used with the argument
1135  * REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN, because we don't know beforehand the number
1136  * of items we are going to output as elements of the array, this function
1137  * will take care to set the array length.
1138  *
1139  * Since it is possible to have multiple array replies pending with unknown
1140  * length, this function guarantees to always set the latest array length
1141  * that was created in a postponed way.
1142  *
1143  * For example in order to output an array like [1,[10,20,30]] we
1144  * could write:
1145  *
1146  * RedisModule_ReplyWithArray(ctx,REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN);
1147  * RedisModule_ReplyWithLongLong(ctx,1);
1148  * RedisModule_ReplyWithArray(ctx,REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN);
1149  * RedisModule_ReplyWithLongLong(ctx,10);
1150  * RedisModule_ReplyWithLongLong(ctx,20);
1151  * RedisModule_ReplyWithLongLong(ctx,30);
1152  * RedisModule_ReplySetArrayLength(ctx,3); // Set len of 10,20,30 array.
1153  * RedisModule_ReplySetArrayLength(ctx,2); // Set len of top array
1154  *
1155  * Note that in the above example there is no reason to postpone the array
1156  * length, since we produce a fixed number of elements, but in the practice
1157  * the code may use an iterator or other ways of creating the output so
1158  * that is not easy to calculate in advance the number of elements.
1159  */
1160 void RM_ReplySetArrayLength(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, long len) {
1161  client *c = moduleGetReplyClient(ctx);
1162  if (c == NULL) return;
1163  if (ctx->postponed_arrays_count == 0) {
1164  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
1165  "API misuse detected in module %s: "
1166  "RedisModule_ReplySetArrayLength() called without previous "
1167  "RedisModule_ReplyWithArray(ctx,REDISMODULE_POSTPONED_ARRAY_LEN) "
1168  "call.", ctx->module->name);
1169  return;
1170  }
1171  ctx->postponed_arrays_count--;
1172  setDeferredMultiBulkLength(c,
1173  ctx->postponed_arrays[ctx->postponed_arrays_count],
1174  len);
1175  if (ctx->postponed_arrays_count == 0) {
1176  zfree(ctx->postponed_arrays);
1177  ctx->postponed_arrays = NULL;
1178  }
1179 }

1243 /* Helper function to replicate MULTI the first time we replicate something
1244  * in the context of a command execution. EXEC will be handled by the
1245  * RedisModuleCommandDispatcher() function. */
1246 void moduleReplicateMultiIfNeeded(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
1247  /* Skip this if client explicitly wrap the command with MULTI, or if
1248  * the module command was called by a script. */
1249  if (ctx->client->flags & (CLIENT_MULTI|CLIENT_LUA)) return;
1250  /* If we already emitted MULTI return ASAP. */
1251  if (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_MULTI_EMITTED) return;
1252  /* If this is a thread safe context, we do not want to wrap commands
1253  * executed into MUTLI/EXEC, they are executed as single commands
1254  * from an external client in essence. */
1255  if (ctx->flags & REDISMODULE_CTX_THREAD_SAFE) return;
1256  execCommandPropagateMulti(ctx->client);
1257  ctx->flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_MULTI_EMITTED;
1258 }
1259 
1260 /* Replicate the specified command and arguments to slaves and AOF, as effect
1261  * of execution of the calling command implementation.
1262  *
1263  * The replicated commands are always wrapped into the MULTI/EXEC that
1264  * contains all the commands replicated in a given module command
1265  * execution. However the commands replicated with RedisModule_Call()
1266  * are the first items, the ones replicated with RedisModule_Replicate()
1267  * will all follow before the EXEC.
1268  *
1269  * Modules should try to use one interface or the other.
1270  *
1271  * This command follows exactly the same interface of RedisModule_Call(),
1272  * so a set of format specifiers must be passed, followed by arguments
1273  * matching the provided format specifiers.
1274  *
1275  * Please refer to RedisModule_Call() for more information.
1276  *
1277  * The command returns REDISMODULE_ERR if the format specifiers are invalid
1278  * or the command name does not belong to a known command. */
1279 int RM_Replicate(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *cmdname, const char *fmt, ...) {
1280  struct redisCommand *cmd;
1281  robj **argv = NULL;
1282  int argc = 0, flags = 0, j;
1283  va_list ap;
1284 
1285  cmd = lookupCommandByCString((char*)cmdname);
1286  if (!cmd) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1287 
1288  /* Create the client and dispatch the command. */
1289  va_start(ap, fmt);
1290  argv = moduleCreateArgvFromUserFormat(cmdname,fmt,&argc,&flags,ap);
1291  va_end(ap);
1292  if (argv == NULL) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1293 
1294  /* Replicate! */
1295  moduleReplicateMultiIfNeeded(ctx);
1296  alsoPropagate(cmd,ctx->client->db->id,argv,argc,
1297  PROPAGATE_AOF|PROPAGATE_REPL);
1298 
1299  /* Release the argv. */
1300  for (j = 0; j < argc; j++) decrRefCount(argv[j]);
1301  zfree(argv);
1302  server.dirty++;
1303  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1304 }
1305 
1306 /* This function will replicate the command exactly as it was invoked
1307  * by the client. Note that this function will not wrap the command into
1308  * a MULTI/EXEC stanza, so it should not be mixed with other replication
1309  * commands.
1310  *
1311  * Basically this form of replication is useful when you want to propagate
1312  * the command to the slaves and AOF file exactly as it was called, since
1313  * the command can just be re-executed to deterministically re-create the
1314  * new state starting from the old one.
1315  *
1316  * The function always returns REDISMODULE_OK. */
1317 int RM_ReplicateVerbatim(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
1318  alsoPropagate(ctx->client->cmd,ctx->client->db->id,
1319  ctx->client->argv,ctx->client->argc,
1320  PROPAGATE_AOF|PROPAGATE_REPL);
1321  server.dirty++;
1322  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1323 }

1329 /* Return the ID of the current client calling the currently active module
1330  * command. The returned ID has a few guarantees:
1331  *
1332  * 1. The ID is different for each different client, so if the same client
1333  * executes a module command multiple times, it can be recognized as
1334  * having the same ID, otherwise the ID will be different.
1335  * 2. The ID increases monotonically. Clients connecting to the server later
1336  * are guaranteed to get IDs greater than any past ID previously seen.
1337  *
1338  * Valid IDs are from 1 to 2^64-1. If 0 is returned it means there is no way
1339  * to fetch the ID in the context the function was currently called. */
1340 unsigned long long RM_GetClientId(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
1341  if (ctx->client == NULL) return 0;
1342  return ctx->client->id;
1343 }

1350 
1351 /* Return the current context's flags. The flags provide information on the
1352  * current request context (whether the client is a Lua script or in a MULTI),
1353  * and about the Redis instance in general, i.e replication and persistence.
1354  *
1355  * The available flags are:
1356  *
1357  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_LUA: The command is running in a Lua script
1358  *
1359  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MULTI: The command is running inside a transaction
1360  *
1361  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MASTER: The Redis instance is a master
1362  *
1363  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_SLAVE: The Redis instance is a slave
1364  *
1365  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_READONLY: The Redis instance is read-only
1366  *
1367  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_CLUSTER: The Redis instance is in cluster mode
1368  *
1369  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_AOF: The Redis instance has AOF enabled
1370  *
1371  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_RDB: The instance has RDB enabled
1372  *
1373  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MAXMEMORY: The instance has Maxmemory set
1374  *
1375  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_EVICT: Maxmemory is set and has an eviction
1376  * policy that may delete keys
1377  *
1378  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_OOM: Redis is out of memory according to the
1379  * maxmemory setting.
1380  *
1381  * * REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_OOM_WARNING: Less than 25% of memory remains before
1382  * reaching the maxmemory level.
1383  */
1384 int RM_GetContextFlags(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
1385 
1386  int flags = 0;
1387  /* Client specific flags */
1388  if (ctx->client) {
1389  if (ctx->client->flags & CLIENT_LUA)
1390  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_LUA;
1391  if (ctx->client->flags & CLIENT_MULTI)
1392  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MULTI;
1393  }
1394 
1395  if (server.cluster_enabled)
1396  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_CLUSTER;
1397 
1398  /* Maxmemory and eviction policy */
1399  if (server.maxmemory > 0) {
1400  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MAXMEMORY;
1401 
1402  if (server.maxmemory_policy != MAXMEMORY_NO_EVICTION)
1403  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_EVICT;
1404  }
1405 
1406  /* Persistence flags */
1407  if (server.aof_state != AOF_OFF)
1408  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_AOF;
1409  if (server.saveparamslen > 0)
1410  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_RDB;
1411 
1412  /* Replication flags */
1413  if (server.masterhost == NULL) {
1414  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_MASTER;
1415  } else {
1416  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_SLAVE;
1417  if (server.repl_slave_ro)
1418  flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_READONLY;
1419  }
1420 
1421  /* OOM flag. */
1422  float level;
1423  int retval = getMaxmemoryState(NULL,NULL,NULL,&level);
1424  if (retval == C_ERR) flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_OOM;
1425  if (level > 0.75) flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_FLAGS_OOM_WARNING;
1426 
1427  return flags;
1428 }

1445 /* Return an handle representing a Redis key, so that it is possible
1446  * to call other APIs with the key handle as argument to perform
1447  * operations on the key.
1448  *
1449  * The return value is the handle representing the key, that must be
1450  * closed with RM_CloseKey().
1451  *
1452  * If the key does not exist and WRITE mode is requested, the handle
1453  * is still returned, since it is possible to perform operations on
1454  * a yet not existing key (that will be created, for example, after
1455  * a list push operation). If the mode is just READ instead, and the
1456  * key does not exist, NULL is returned. However it is still safe to
1457  * call RedisModule_CloseKey() and RedisModule_KeyType() on a NULL
1458  * value. */
1459 void *RM_OpenKey(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, robj *keyname, int mode) {
1460  RedisModuleKey *kp;
1461  robj *value;
1462 
1463  if (mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE) {
1464  value = lookupKeyWrite(ctx->client->db,keyname);
1465  } else {
1466  value = lookupKeyRead(ctx->client->db,keyname);
1467  if (value == NULL) {
1468  return NULL;
1469  }
1470  }
1471 
1472  /* Setup the key handle. */
1473  kp = zmalloc(sizeof(*kp));
1474  kp->ctx = ctx;
1475  kp->db = ctx->client->db;
1476  kp->key = keyname;
1477  incrRefCount(keyname);
1478  kp->value = value;
1479  kp->iter = NULL;
1480  kp->mode = mode;
1481  zsetKeyReset(kp);
1482  autoMemoryAdd(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_KEY,kp);
1483  return (void*)kp;
1484 }

1486 /* Close a key handle. */
1487 void RM_CloseKey(RedisModuleKey *key) {
1488  if (key == NULL) return;
1489  if (key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE) signalModifiedKey(key->db,key->key);
1490  /* TODO: if (key->iter) RM_KeyIteratorStop(kp); */
1491  RM_ZsetRangeStop(key);
1492  decrRefCount(key->key);
1493  autoMemoryFreed(key->ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_KEY,key);
1494  zfree(key);
1495 }

1497 /* Return the type of the key. If the key pointer is NULL then
1498  * REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_EMPTY is returned. */
1499 int RM_KeyType(RedisModuleKey *key) {
1500  if (key == NULL || key->value == NULL) return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_EMPTY;
1501  /* We map between defines so that we are free to change the internal
1502  * defines as desired. */
1503  switch(key->value->type) {
1504  case OBJ_STRING: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_STRING;
1505  case OBJ_LIST: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_LIST;
1506  case OBJ_SET: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_SET;
1507  case OBJ_ZSET: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_ZSET;
1508  case OBJ_HASH: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_HASH;
1509  case OBJ_MODULE: return REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_MODULE;
1510  default: return 0;
1511  }
1512 }

1514 /* Return the length of the value associated with the key.
1515  * For strings this is the length of the string. For all the other types
1516  * is the number of elements (just counting keys for hashes).

1518  * If the key pointer is NULL or the key is empty, zero is returned. */
1519 size_t RM_ValueLength(RedisModuleKey *key) {

1523  case OBJ_LIST: return listTypeLength(key->value);
1524  case OBJ_SET: return setTypeSize(key->value);

1558 /* Return the key expire value, as milliseconds of remaining TTL.
1559  * If no TTL is associated with the key or if the key is empty,

1561 mstime_t RM_GetExpire(RedisModuleKey *key) {

1568 /* Set a new expire for the key. If the special expire
1569  * REDISMODULE_NO_EXPIRE is set, the expire is cancelled if there was

1571  *
1572  * Note that the expire must be provided as a positive integer representing
1573  * the number of milliseconds of TTL the key should have.
1574  *

1581  expire += mstime();

1604 
1605 /* Prepare the key associated string value for DMA access, and returns
1606  * a pointer and size (by reference), that the user can use to read or
1607  * modify the string in-place accessing it directly via pointer.
1608  *
1609  * The 'mode' is composed by bitwise OR-ing the following flags:
1610  *
1611  * REDISMODULE_READ -- Read access
1612  * REDISMODULE_WRITE -- Write access
1613  *
1614  * If the DMA is not requested for writing, the pointer returned should
1615  * only be accessed in a read-only fashion.
1616  *
1617  * On error (wrong type) NULL is returned.
1618  *
1619  * DMA access rules:
1620  *
1621  * 1. No other key writing function should be called since the moment
1622  * the pointer is obtained, for all the time we want to use DMA access
1623  * to read or modify the string.
1624  *
1625  * 2. Each time RM_StringTruncate() is called, to continue with the DMA
1626  * access, RM_StringDMA() should be called again to re-obtain
1627  * a new pointer and length.
1628  *
1629  * 3. If the returned pointer is not NULL, but the length is zero, no
1630  * byte can be touched (the string is empty, or the key itself is empty)
1631  * so a RM_StringTruncate() call should be used if there is to enlarge
1632  * the string, and later call StringDMA() again to get the pointer.
1633  */
1634 char *RM_StringDMA(RedisModuleKey *key, size_t *len, int mode) {
1635  /* We need to return *some* pointer for empty keys, we just return
1636  * a string literal pointer, that is the advantage to be mapped into
1637  * a read only memory page, so the module will segfault if a write
1638  * attempt is performed. */
1639  char *emptystring = "<dma-empty-string>";
1640  if (key->value == NULL) {
1641  *len = 0;
1642  return emptystring;
1643  }
1644 
1645  if (key->value->type != OBJ_STRING) return NULL;
1646 
1647  /* For write access, and even for read access if the object is encoded,
1648  * we unshare the string (that has the side effect of decoding it). */
1649  if ((mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE) || key->value->encoding != OBJ_ENCODING_RAW)
1650  key->value = dbUnshareStringValue(key->db, key->key, key->value);
1651 
1652  *len = sdslen(key->value->ptr);
1653  return key->value->ptr;
1654 }
1655 
1656 /* If the string is open for writing and is of string type, resize it, padding
1657  * with zero bytes if the new length is greater than the old one.
1658  *
1659  * After this call, RM_StringDMA() must be called again to continue
1660  * DMA access with the new pointer.
1661  *
1662  * The function returns REDISMODULE_OK on success, and REDISMODULE_ERR on
1663  * error, that is, the key is not open for writing, is not a string
1664  * or resizing for more than 512 MB is requested.
1665  *
1666  * If the key is empty, a string key is created with the new string value
1667  * unless the new length value requested is zero. */
1668 int RM_StringTruncate(RedisModuleKey *key, size_t newlen) {
1669  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1670  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_STRING) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1671  if (newlen > 512*1024*1024) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1672 
1673  /* Empty key and new len set to 0. Just return REDISMODULE_OK without
1674  * doing anything. */
1675  if (key->value == NULL && newlen == 0) return REDISMODULE_OK;
1676 
1677  if (key->value == NULL) {
1678  /* Empty key: create it with the new size. */
1679  robj *o = createObject(OBJ_STRING,sdsnewlen(NULL, newlen));
1680  setKey(key->db,key->key,o);
1681  key->value = o;
1682  decrRefCount(o);
1683  } else {
1684  /* Unshare and resize. */
1685  key->value = dbUnshareStringValue(key->db, key->key, key->value);
1686  size_t curlen = sdslen(key->value->ptr);
1687  if (newlen > curlen) {
1688  key->value->ptr = sdsgrowzero(key->value->ptr,newlen);
1689  } else if (newlen < curlen) {
1690  sdsrange(key->value->ptr,0,newlen-1);
1691  /* If the string is too wasteful, reallocate it. */
1692  if (sdslen(key->value->ptr) < sdsavail(key->value->ptr))
1693  key->value->ptr = sdsRemoveFreeSpace(key->value->ptr);
1694  }
1695  }
1696  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1697 }

1703 /* Push an element into a list, on head or tail depending on 'where' argument.
1704  * If the key pointer is about an empty key opened for writing, the key
1705  * is created. On error (key opened for read-only operations or of the wrong

1712  (where == REDISMODULE_LIST_HEAD) ? QUICKLIST_HEAD : QUICKLIST_TAIL);
1713  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1714 }

1716 /* Pop an element from the list, and returns it as a module string object
1717  * that the user should be free with RM_FreeString() or by enabling
1718  * automatic memory. 'where' specifies if the element should be popped from
1719  * head or tail. The command returns NULL if:
1720  * 1) The list is empty.
1721  * 2) The key was not open for writing.
1722  * 3) The key is not a list. */
1723 RedisModuleString *RM_ListPop(RedisModuleKey *key, int where) {

1725  key->value == NULL ||

1728  (where == REDISMODULE_LIST_HEAD) ? QUICKLIST_HEAD : QUICKLIST_TAIL);

1740 /* Conversion from/to public flags of the Modules API and our private flags,
1741  * so that we have everything decoupled. */
1742 int RM_ZsetAddFlagsToCoreFlags(int flags) {
1743  int retflags = 0;
1744  if (flags & REDISMODULE_ZADD_XX) retflags |= ZADD_XX;
1745  if (flags & REDISMODULE_ZADD_NX) retflags |= ZADD_NX;
1746  return retflags;
1747 }
1748 
1749 /* See previous function comment. */
1750 int RM_ZsetAddFlagsFromCoreFlags(int flags) {
1751  int retflags = 0;
1752  if (flags & ZADD_ADDED) retflags |= REDISMODULE_ZADD_ADDED;
1753  if (flags & ZADD_UPDATED) retflags |= REDISMODULE_ZADD_UPDATED;
1754  if (flags & ZADD_NOP) retflags |= REDISMODULE_ZADD_NOP;
1755  return retflags;
1756 }

1758 /* Add a new element into a sorted set, with the specified 'score'.
1759  * If the element already exists, the score is updated.
1760  *
1761  * A new sorted set is created at value if the key is an empty open key
1762  * setup for writing.
1763  *
1764  * Additional flags can be passed to the function via a pointer, the flags
1765  * are both used to receive input and to communicate state when the function
1766  * returns. 'flagsptr' can be NULL if no special flags are used.
1767  *
1768  * The input flags are:
1769  *
1770  * REDISMODULE_ZADD_XX: Element must already exist. Do nothing otherwise.
1771  * REDISMODULE_ZADD_NX: Element must not exist. Do nothing otherwise.
1772  *
1773  * The output flags are:
1774  *
1775  * REDISMODULE_ZADD_ADDED: The new element was added to the sorted set.
1776  * REDISMODULE_ZADD_UPDATED: The score of the element was updated.
1777  * REDISMODULE_ZADD_NOP: No operation was performed because XX or NX flags.
1778  *
1779  * On success the function returns REDISMODULE_OK. On the following errors
1780  * REDISMODULE_ERR is returned:
1781  *
1782  * * The key was not opened for writing.
1783  * * The key is of the wrong type.
1784  * * 'score' double value is not a number (NaN).
1785  */
1786 int RM_ZsetAdd(RedisModuleKey *key, double score, RedisModuleString *ele, int *flagsptr) {
1787  int flags = 0;
1788  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1789  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1790  if (key->value == NULL) moduleCreateEmptyKey(key,REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_ZSET);
1791  if (flagsptr) flags = RM_ZsetAddFlagsToCoreFlags(*flagsptr);
1792  if (zsetAdd(key->value,score,ele->ptr,&flags,NULL) == 0) {
1793  if (flagsptr) *flagsptr = 0;
1794  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1795  }
1796  if (flagsptr) *flagsptr = RM_ZsetAddFlagsFromCoreFlags(flags);
1797  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1798 }

1800 /* This function works exactly like RM_ZsetAdd(), but instead of setting
1801  * a new score, the score of the existing element is incremented, or if the
1802  * element does not already exist, it is added assuming the old score was
1803  * zero.
1804  *
1805  * The input and output flags, and the return value, have the same exact
1806  * meaning, with the only difference that this function will return
1807  * REDISMODULE_ERR even when 'score' is a valid double number, but adding it
1808  * to the existing score results into a NaN (not a number) condition.
1809  *
1810  * This function has an additional field 'newscore', if not NULL is filled
1811  * with the new score of the element after the increment, if no error
1812  * is returned. */
1813 int RM_ZsetIncrby(RedisModuleKey *key, double score, RedisModuleString *ele, int *flagsptr, double *newscore) {
1814  int flags = 0;
1815  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1816  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1817  if (key->value == NULL) moduleCreateEmptyKey(key,REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_ZSET);
1818  if (flagsptr) flags = RM_ZsetAddFlagsToCoreFlags(*flagsptr);
1819  flags |= ZADD_INCR;
1820  if (zsetAdd(key->value,score,ele->ptr,&flags,newscore) == 0) {
1821  if (flagsptr) *flagsptr = 0;
1822  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1823  }
1824  /* zsetAdd() may signal back that the resulting score is not a number. */
1825  if (flagsptr && (*flagsptr & ZADD_NAN)) {
1826  *flagsptr = 0;
1827  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1828  }
1829  if (flagsptr) *flagsptr = RM_ZsetAddFlagsFromCoreFlags(flags);
1830  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1831 }

1833 /* Remove the specified element from the sorted set.
1834  * The function returns REDISMODULE_OK on success, and REDISMODULE_ERR
1835  * on one of the following conditions:
1836  *
1837  * * The key was not opened for writing.
1838  * * The key is of the wrong type.
1839  *
1840  * The return value does NOT indicate the fact the element was really
1841  * removed (since it existed) or not, just if the function was executed
1842  * with success.
1843  *
1844  * In order to know if the element was removed, the additional argument
1845  * 'deleted' must be passed, that populates the integer by reference
1846  * setting it to 1 or 0 depending on the outcome of the operation.
1847  * The 'deleted' argument can be NULL if the caller is not interested
1848  * to know if the element was really removed.
1849  *
1850  * Empty keys will be handled correctly by doing nothing. */
1851 int RM_ZsetRem(RedisModuleKey *key, RedisModuleString *ele, int *deleted) {
1852  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1853  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1854  if (key->value != NULL && zsetDel(key->value,ele->ptr)) {
1855  if (deleted) *deleted = 1;
1856  } else {
1857  if (deleted) *deleted = 0;
1858  }
1859  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1860 }

1862 /* On success retrieve the double score associated at the sorted set element
1863  * 'ele' and returns REDISMODULE_OK. Otherwise REDISMODULE_ERR is returned
1864  * to signal one of the following conditions:
1865  *
1866  * * There is no such element 'ele' in the sorted set.
1867  * * The key is not a sorted set.
1868  * * The key is an open empty key.
1869  */
1870 int RM_ZsetScore(RedisModuleKey *key, RedisModuleString *ele, double *score) {

1872  if (key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1873  if (zsetScore(key->value,ele->ptr,score) == C_ERR) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1874  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1875 }

1903 /* Helper function for RM_ZsetFirstInScoreRange() and RM_ZsetLastInScoreRange().
1904  * Setup the sorted set iteration according to the specified score range
1905  * (see the functions calling it for more info). If 'first' is true the
1906  * first element in the range is used as a starting point for the iterator
1907  * otherwise the last. Return REDISMODULE_OK on success otherwise
1908  * REDISMODULE_ERR. */
1909 int zsetInitScoreRange(RedisModuleKey *key, double min, double max, int minex, int maxex, int first) {
1910  if (!key->value || key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1911 
1912  RM_ZsetRangeStop(key);
1913  key->ztype = REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_SCORE;
1914  key->zer = 0;
1915 
1916  /* Setup the range structure used by the sorted set core implementation
1917  * in order to seek at the specified element. */
1918  zrangespec *zrs = &key->zrs;
1919  zrs->min = min;
1920  zrs->max = max;
1921  zrs->minex = minex;
1922  zrs->maxex = maxex;
1923 
1924  if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_ZIPLIST) {
1925  key->zcurrent = first ? zzlFirstInRange(key->value->ptr,zrs) :
1926  zzlLastInRange(key->value->ptr,zrs);
1927  } else if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_SKIPLIST) {
1928  zset *zs = key->value->ptr;
1929  zskiplist *zsl = zs->zsl;
1930  key->zcurrent = first ? zslFirstInRange(zsl,zrs) :
1931  zslLastInRange(zsl,zrs);
1932  } else {
1933  serverPanic("Unsupported zset encoding");
1934  }
1935  if (key->zcurrent == NULL) key->zer = 1;
1936  return REDISMODULE_OK;
1937 }

1940  * range. Returns REDISMODULE_OK if the iterator was correctly initialized
1941  * otherwise REDISMODULE_ERR is returned in the following conditions:
1942  *
1943  * 1. The value stored at key is not a sorted set or the key is empty.
1944  *
1945  * The range is specified according to the two double values 'min' and 'max'.
1946  * Both can be infinite using the following two macros:
1947  *
1948  * REDISMODULE_POSITIVE_INFINITE for positive infinite value
1949  * REDISMODULE_NEGATIVE_INFINITE for negative infinite value
1950  *
1951  * 'minex' and 'maxex' parameters, if true, respectively setup a range
1952  * where the min and max value are exclusive (not included) instead of
1953  * inclusive. */
1954 int RM_ZsetFirstInScoreRange(RedisModuleKey *key, double min, double max, int minex, int maxex) {

1964 /* Helper function for RM_ZsetFirstInLexRange() and RM_ZsetLastInLexRange().
1965  * Setup the sorted set iteration according to the specified lexicographical
1966  * range (see the functions calling it for more info). If 'first' is true the
1967  * first element in the range is used as a starting point for the iterator
1968  * otherwise the last. Return REDISMODULE_OK on success otherwise
1969  * REDISMODULE_ERR.
1970  *
1971  * Note that this function takes 'min' and 'max' in the same form of the
1972  * Redis ZRANGEBYLEX command. */
1973 int zsetInitLexRange(RedisModuleKey *key, RedisModuleString *min, RedisModuleString *max, int first) {
1974  if (!key->value || key->value->type != OBJ_ZSET) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1975 
1976  RM_ZsetRangeStop(key);
1977  key->zer = 0;
1978 
1979  /* Setup the range structure used by the sorted set core implementation
1980  * in order to seek at the specified element. */
1981  zlexrangespec *zlrs = &key->zlrs;
1982  if (zslParseLexRange(min, max, zlrs) == C_ERR) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
1983 
1984  /* Set the range type to lex only after successfully parsing the range,
1985  * otherwise we don't want the zlexrangespec to be freed. */
1986  key->ztype = REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_LEX;
1987 
1988  if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_ZIPLIST) {
1989  key->zcurrent = first ? zzlFirstInLexRange(key->value->ptr,zlrs) :
1990  zzlLastInLexRange(key->value->ptr,zlrs);
1991  } else if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_SKIPLIST) {
1992  zset *zs = key->value->ptr;
1993  zskiplist *zsl = zs->zsl;
1994  key->zcurrent = first ? zslFirstInLexRange(zsl,zlrs) :
1995  zslLastInLexRange(zsl,zlrs);
1996  } else {
1997  serverPanic("Unsupported zset encoding");
1998  }
1999  if (key->zcurrent == NULL) key->zer = 1;
2000 
2001  return REDISMODULE_OK;
2002 }

2026 /* Return the current sorted set element of an active sorted set iterator
2027  * or NULL if the range specified in the iterator does not include any
2028  * element. */
2029 RedisModuleString *RM_ZsetRangeCurrentElement(RedisModuleKey *key, double *score) {

2031

2053 /* Go to the next element of the sorted set iterator. Returns 1 if there was
2054  * a next element, 0 if we are already at the latest element or the range
2055  * does not include any item at all. */
2056 int RM_ZsetRangeNext(RedisModuleKey *key) {
2057  if (!key->ztype || !key->zcurrent) return 0; /* No active iterator. */
2058 
2059  if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_ZIPLIST) {
2060  unsigned char *zl = key->value->ptr;
2061  unsigned char *eptr = key->zcurrent;
2062  unsigned char *next;
2063  next = ziplistNext(zl,eptr); /* Skip element. */
2064  if (next) next = ziplistNext(zl,next); /* Skip score. */
2065  if (next == NULL) {
2066  key->zer = 1;
2067  return 0;
2068  } else {
2069  /* Are we still within the range? */
2070  if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_SCORE) {
2071  /* Fetch the next element score for the
2072  * range check. */
2073  unsigned char *saved_next = next;
2074  next = ziplistNext(zl,next); /* Skip next element. */
2075  double score = zzlGetScore(next); /* Obtain the next score. */
2076  if (!zslValueLteMax(score,&key->zrs)) {
2077  key->zer = 1;
2078  return 0;
2079  }
2080  next = saved_next;
2081  } else if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_LEX) {
2082  if (!zzlLexValueLteMax(next,&key->zlrs)) {
2083  key->zer = 1;
2084  return 0;
2085  }
2086  }
2087  key->zcurrent = next;
2088  return 1;
2089  }
2090  } else if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_SKIPLIST) {
2091  zskiplistNode *ln = key->zcurrent, *next = ln->level[0].forward;
2092  if (next == NULL) {
2093  key->zer = 1;
2094  return 0;
2095  } else {
2096  /* Are we still within the range? */
2097  if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_SCORE &&
2098  !zslValueLteMax(next->score,&key->zrs))
2099  {
2100  key->zer = 1;
2101  return 0;
2102  } else if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_LEX) {
2103  if (!zslLexValueLteMax(next->ele,&key->zlrs)) {
2104  key->zer = 1;
2105  return 0;
2106  }
2107  }
2108  key->zcurrent = next;
2109  return 1;
2110  }
2111  } else {
2112  serverPanic("Unsupported zset encoding");
2113  }
2114 }
2115 
2116 /* Go to the previous element of the sorted set iterator. Returns 1 if there was
2117  * a previous element, 0 if we are already at the first element or the range
2118  * does not include any item at all. */
2119 int RM_ZsetRangePrev(RedisModuleKey *key) {
2120  if (!key->ztype || !key->zcurrent) return 0; /* No active iterator. */
2121 
2122  if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_ZIPLIST) {
2123  unsigned char *zl = key->value->ptr;
2124  unsigned char *eptr = key->zcurrent;
2125  unsigned char *prev;
2126  prev = ziplistPrev(zl,eptr); /* Go back to previous score. */
2127  if (prev) prev = ziplistPrev(zl,prev); /* Back to previous ele. */
2128  if (prev == NULL) {
2129  key->zer = 1;
2130  return 0;
2131  } else {
2132  /* Are we still within the range? */
2133  if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_SCORE) {
2134  /* Fetch the previous element score for the
2135  * range check. */
2136  unsigned char *saved_prev = prev;
2137  prev = ziplistNext(zl,prev); /* Skip element to get the score.*/
2138  double score = zzlGetScore(prev); /* Obtain the prev score. */
2139  if (!zslValueGteMin(score,&key->zrs)) {
2140  key->zer = 1;
2141  return 0;
2142  }
2143  prev = saved_prev;
2144  } else if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_LEX) {
2145  if (!zzlLexValueGteMin(prev,&key->zlrs)) {
2146  key->zer = 1;
2147  return 0;
2148  }
2149  }
2150  key->zcurrent = prev;
2151  return 1;
2152  }
2153  } else if (key->value->encoding == OBJ_ENCODING_SKIPLIST) {
2154  zskiplistNode *ln = key->zcurrent, *prev = ln->backward;
2155  if (prev == NULL) {
2156  key->zer = 1;
2157  return 0;
2158  } else {
2159  /* Are we still within the range? */
2160  if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_SCORE &&
2161  !zslValueGteMin(prev->score,&key->zrs))
2162  {
2163  key->zer = 1;
2164  return 0;
2165  } else if (key->ztype == REDISMODULE_ZSET_RANGE_LEX) {
2166  if (!zslLexValueGteMin(prev->ele,&key->zlrs)) {
2167  key->zer = 1;
2168  return 0;
2169  }
2170  }
2171  key->zcurrent = prev;
2172  return 1;
2173  }
2174  } else {
2175  serverPanic("Unsupported zset encoding");
2176  }
2177 }

2179 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
2180  * Key API for Hash type
2181  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
2182 
2183 /* Set the field of the specified hash field to the specified value.
2184  * If the key is an empty key open for writing, it is created with an empty
2185  * hash value, in order to set the specified field.
2186  *
2187  * The function is variadic and the user must specify pairs of field
2188  * names and values, both as RedisModuleString pointers (unless the
2189  * CFIELD option is set, see later). At the end of the field/value-ptr pairs,
2190  * NULL must be specified as last argument to signal the end of the arguments
2191  * in the variadic function.
2192  *
2193  * Example to set the hash argv[1] to the value argv[2]:
2194  *
2195  * RedisModule_HashSet(key,REDISMODULE_HASH_NONE,argv[1],argv[2],NULL);
2196  *
2197  * The function can also be used in order to delete fields (if they exist)
2198  * by setting them to the specified value of REDISMODULE_HASH_DELETE:
2199  *
2200  * RedisModule_HashSet(key,REDISMODULE_HASH_NONE,argv[1],
2201  * REDISMODULE_HASH_DELETE,NULL);
2202  *
2203  * The behavior of the command changes with the specified flags, that can be
2204  * set to REDISMODULE_HASH_NONE if no special behavior is needed.
2205  *
2206  * REDISMODULE_HASH_NX: The operation is performed only if the field was not
2207  * already existing in the hash.
2208  * REDISMODULE_HASH_XX: The operation is performed only if the field was
2209  * already existing, so that a new value could be
2210  * associated to an existing filed, but no new fields
2211  * are created.
2212  * REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS: The field names passed are null terminated C
2213  * strings instead of RedisModuleString objects.
2214  *
2215  * Unless NX is specified, the command overwrites the old field value with
2216  * the new one.
2217  *
2218  * When using REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS, field names are reported using
2219  * normal C strings, so for example to delete the field "foo" the following
2220  * code can be used:
2221  *
2222  * RedisModule_HashSet(key,REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS,"foo",
2223  * REDISMODULE_HASH_DELETE,NULL);
2224  *
2225  * Return value:
2226  *
2227  * The number of fields updated (that may be less than the number of fields
2228  * specified because of the XX or NX options).
2229  *
2230  * In the following case the return value is always zero:
2231  *
2232  * * The key was not open for writing.
2233  * * The key was associated with a non Hash value.
2234  */
2235 int RM_HashSet(RedisModuleKey *key, int flags, ...) {
2236  va_list ap;
2237  if (!(key->mode & REDISMODULE_WRITE)) return 0;
2238  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_HASH) return 0;
2239  if (key->value == NULL) moduleCreateEmptyKey(key,REDISMODULE_KEYTYPE_HASH);
2240 
2241  int updated = 0;
2242  va_start(ap, flags);
2243  while(1) {
2244  RedisModuleString *field, *value;
2245  /* Get the field and value objects. */
2246  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) {
2247  char *cfield = va_arg(ap,char*);
2248  if (cfield == NULL) break;
2249  field = createRawStringObject(cfield,strlen(cfield));
2250  } else {
2251  field = va_arg(ap,RedisModuleString*);
2252  if (field == NULL) break;
2253  }
2254  value = va_arg(ap,RedisModuleString*);
2255 
2256  /* Handle XX and NX */
2257  if (flags & (REDISMODULE_HASH_XX|REDISMODULE_HASH_NX)) {
2258  int exists = hashTypeExists(key->value, field->ptr);
2259  if (((flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_XX) && !exists) ||
2260  ((flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_NX) && exists))
2261  {
2262  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) decrRefCount(field);
2263  continue;
2264  }
2265  }
2266 
2267  /* Handle deletion if value is REDISMODULE_HASH_DELETE. */
2268  if (value == REDISMODULE_HASH_DELETE) {
2269  updated += hashTypeDelete(key->value, field->ptr);
2270  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) decrRefCount(field);
2271  continue;
2272  }
2273 
2274  int low_flags = HASH_SET_COPY;
2275  /* If CFIELDS is active, we can pass the ownership of the
2276  * SDS object to the low level function that sets the field
2277  * to avoid a useless copy. */
2278  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS)
2279  low_flags |= HASH_SET_TAKE_FIELD;
2280 
2281  robj *argv[2] = {field,value};
2282  hashTypeTryConversion(key->value,argv,0,1);
2283  updated += hashTypeSet(key->value, field->ptr, value->ptr, low_flags);
2284 
2285  /* If CFIELDS is active, SDS string ownership is now of hashTypeSet(),
2286  * however we still have to release the 'field' object shell. */
2287  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) {
2288  field->ptr = NULL; /* Prevent the SDS string from being freed. */
2289  decrRefCount(field);
2290  }
2291  }
2292  va_end(ap);
2293  moduleDelKeyIfEmpty(key);
2294  return updated;
2295 }
2296 
2297 /* Get fields from an hash value. This function is called using a variable
2298  * number of arguments, alternating a field name (as a StringRedisModule
2299  * pointer) with a pointer to a StringRedisModule pointer, that is set to the
2300  * value of the field if the field exist, or NULL if the field did not exist.
2301  * At the end of the field/value-ptr pairs, NULL must be specified as last
2302  * argument to signal the end of the arguments in the variadic function.
2303  *
2304  * This is an example usage:
2305  *
2306  * RedisModuleString *first, *second;
2307  * RedisModule_HashGet(mykey,REDISMODULE_HASH_NONE,argv[1],&first,
2308  * argv[2],&second,NULL);
2309  *
2310  * As with RedisModule_HashSet() the behavior of the command can be specified
2311  * passing flags different than REDISMODULE_HASH_NONE:
2312  *
2313  * REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELD: field names as null terminated C strings.
2314  *
2315  * REDISMODULE_HASH_EXISTS: instead of setting the value of the field
2316  * expecting a RedisModuleString pointer to pointer, the function just
2317  * reports if the field esists or not and expects an integer pointer
2318  * as the second element of each pair.
2319  *
2320  * Example of REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELD:
2321  *
2322  * RedisModuleString *username, *hashedpass;
2323  * RedisModule_HashGet(mykey,"username",&username,"hp",&hashedpass, NULL);
2324  *
2325  * Example of REDISMODULE_HASH_EXISTS:
2326  *
2327  * int exists;
2328  * RedisModule_HashGet(mykey,argv[1],&exists,NULL);
2329  *
2330  * The function returns REDISMODULE_OK on success and REDISMODULE_ERR if
2331  * the key is not an hash value.
2332  *
2333  * Memory management:
2334  *
2335  * The returned RedisModuleString objects should be released with
2336  * RedisModule_FreeString(), or by enabling automatic memory management.
2337  */
2338 int RM_HashGet(RedisModuleKey *key, int flags, ...) {
2339  va_list ap;
2340  if (key->value && key->value->type != OBJ_HASH) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
2341 
2342  va_start(ap, flags);
2343  while(1) {
2344  RedisModuleString *field, **valueptr;
2345  int *existsptr;
2346  /* Get the field object and the value pointer to pointer. */
2347  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) {
2348  char *cfield = va_arg(ap,char*);
2349  if (cfield == NULL) break;
2350  field = createRawStringObject(cfield,strlen(cfield));
2351  } else {
2352  field = va_arg(ap,RedisModuleString*);
2353  if (field == NULL) break;
2354  }
2355 
2356  /* Query the hash for existence or value object. */
2357  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_EXISTS) {
2358  existsptr = va_arg(ap,int*);
2359  if (key->value)
2360  *existsptr = hashTypeExists(key->value,field->ptr);
2361  else
2362  *existsptr = 0;
2363  } else {
2364  valueptr = va_arg(ap,RedisModuleString**);
2365  if (key->value) {
2366  *valueptr = hashTypeGetValueObject(key->value,field->ptr);
2367  if (*valueptr) {
2368  robj *decoded = getDecodedObject(*valueptr);
2369  decrRefCount(*valueptr);
2370  *valueptr = decoded;
2371  }
2372  if (*valueptr)
2373  autoMemoryAdd(key->ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_STRING,*valueptr);
2374  } else {
2375  *valueptr = NULL;
2376  }
2377  }
2378 
2379  /* Cleanup */
2380  if (flags & REDISMODULE_HASH_CFIELDS) decrRefCount(field);
2381  }
2382  va_end(ap);
2383  return REDISMODULE_OK;
2384 }

2390 /* Create a new RedisModuleCallReply object. The processing of the reply
2391  * is lazy, the object is just populated with the raw protocol and later
2392  * is processed as needed. Initially we just make sure to set the right
2393  * reply type, which is extremely cheap to do. */
2394 RedisModuleCallReply *moduleCreateCallReplyFromProto(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, sds proto) {
2395  RedisModuleCallReply *reply = zmalloc(sizeof(*reply));
2396  reply->ctx = ctx;
2397  reply->proto = proto;
2398  reply->protolen = sdslen(proto);
2399  reply->flags = REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE; /* Lazy parsing. */
2400  switch(proto[0]) {
2401  case '$':
2402  case '+': reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_STRING; break;
2403  case '-': reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_ERROR; break;
2404  case ':': reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_INTEGER; break;
2405  case '*': reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_ARRAY; break;
2406  default: reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_UNKNOWN; break;
2407  }
2408  if ((proto[0] == '*' || proto[0] == '$') && proto[1] == '-')
2409  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_NULL;
2410  return reply;
2411 }

2413 void moduleParseCallReply_Int(RedisModuleCallReply *reply);
2414 void moduleParseCallReply_BulkString(RedisModuleCallReply *reply);
2415 void moduleParseCallReply_SimpleString(RedisModuleCallReply *reply);
2416 void moduleParseCallReply_Array(RedisModuleCallReply *reply);
2417 
2418 /* Do nothing if REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE is false, otherwise
2419  * use the protcol of the reply in reply->proto in order to fill the
2420  * reply with parsed data according to the reply type. */
2421 void moduleParseCallReply(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2422  if (!(reply->flags & REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE)) return;
2423  reply->flags &= ~REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE;
2424 
2425  switch(reply->proto[0]) {
2426  case ':': moduleParseCallReply_Int(reply); break;
2427  case '$': moduleParseCallReply_BulkString(reply); break;
2428  case '-': /* handled by next item. */
2429  case '+': moduleParseCallReply_SimpleString(reply); break;
2430  case '*': moduleParseCallReply_Array(reply); break;
2431  }
2432 }
2433 
2434 void moduleParseCallReply_Int(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2435  char *proto = reply->proto;
2436  char *p = strchr(proto+1,'\r');
2437 
2438  string2ll(proto+1,p-proto-1,&reply->val.ll);
2439  reply->protolen = p-proto+2;
2440  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_INTEGER;
2441 }
2442 
2443 void moduleParseCallReply_BulkString(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2444  char *proto = reply->proto;
2445  char *p = strchr(proto+1,'\r');
2446  long long bulklen;
2447 
2448  string2ll(proto+1,p-proto-1,&bulklen);
2449  if (bulklen == -1) {
2450  reply->protolen = p-proto+2;
2451  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_NULL;
2452  } else {
2453  reply->val.str = p+2;
2454  reply->len = bulklen;
2455  reply->protolen = p-proto+2+bulklen+2;
2456  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_STRING;
2457  }
2458 }
2459 
2460 void moduleParseCallReply_SimpleString(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2461  char *proto = reply->proto;
2462  char *p = strchr(proto+1,'\r');
2463 
2464  reply->val.str = proto+1;
2465  reply->len = p-proto-1;
2466  reply->protolen = p-proto+2;
2467  reply->type = proto[0] == '+' ? REDISMODULE_REPLY_STRING :
2468  REDISMODULE_REPLY_ERROR;
2469 }
2470 
2471 void moduleParseCallReply_Array(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2472  char *proto = reply->proto;
2473  char *p = strchr(proto+1,'\r');
2474  long long arraylen, j;
2475 
2476  string2ll(proto+1,p-proto-1,&arraylen);
2477  p += 2;
2478 
2479  if (arraylen == -1) {
2480  reply->protolen = p-proto;
2481  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_NULL;
2482  return;
2483  }
2484 
2485  reply->val.array = zmalloc(sizeof(RedisModuleCallReply)*arraylen);
2486  reply->len = arraylen;
2487  for (j = 0; j < arraylen; j++) {
2488  RedisModuleCallReply *ele = reply->val.array+j;
2489  ele->flags = REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_NESTED |
2490  REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE;
2491  ele->proto = p;
2492  ele->ctx = reply->ctx;
2493  moduleParseCallReply(ele);
2494  p += ele->protolen;
2495  }
2496  reply->protolen = p-proto;
2497  reply->type = REDISMODULE_REPLY_ARRAY;
2498 }

2500 /* Free a Call reply and all the nested replies it contains if it's an
2501  * array. */
2502 void RM_FreeCallReply_Rec(RedisModuleCallReply *reply, int freenested){
2503  /* Don't free nested replies by default: the user must always free the
2504  * toplevel reply. However be gentle and don't crash if the module
2505  * misuses the API. */
2506  if (!freenested && reply->flags & REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_NESTED) return;
2507 
2508  if (!(reply->flags & REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_TOPARSE)) {
2509  if (reply->type == REDISMODULE_REPLY_ARRAY) {
2510  size_t j;
2511  for (j = 0; j < reply->len; j++)
2512  RM_FreeCallReply_Rec(reply->val.array+j,1);
2513  zfree(reply->val.array);
2514  }
2515  }
2516 
2517  /* For nested replies, we don't free reply->proto (which if not NULL
2518  * references the parent reply->proto buffer), nor the structure
2519  * itself which is allocated as an array of structures, and is freed
2520  * when the array value is released. */
2521  if (!(reply->flags & REDISMODULE_REPLYFLAG_NESTED)) {
2522  if (reply->proto) sdsfree(reply->proto);
2523  zfree(reply);
2524  }
2525 }

2528  * to have the first level function to return on nested replies, but only
2529  * if called by the module API. */
2530 void RM_FreeCallReply(RedisModuleCallReply *reply) {
2531 
2532  RedisModuleCtx *ctx = reply->ctx;
2533  RM_FreeCallReply_Rec(reply,0);
2534  autoMemoryFreed(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_REPLY,reply);
2535 }

2598 /* Returns an array of robj pointers, and populates *argc with the number
2599  * of items, by parsing the format specifier "fmt" as described for
2600  * the RM_Call(), RM_Replicate() and other module APIs.
2601  *
2602  * The integer pointed by 'flags' is populated with flags according
2603  * to special modifiers in "fmt". For now only one exists:
2604  *
2605  * "!" -> REDISMODULE_ARGV_REPLICATE
2606  *
2607  * On error (format specifier error) NULL is returned and nothing is
2608  * allocated. On success the argument vector is returned. */
2609 
2610 #define REDISMODULE_ARGV_REPLICATE (1<<0)
2611 
2612 robj **moduleCreateArgvFromUserFormat(const char *cmdname, const char *fmt, int *argcp, int *flags, va_list ap) {
2613  int argc = 0, argv_size, j;
2614  robj **argv = NULL;
2615 
2616  /* As a first guess to avoid useless reallocations, size argv to
2617  * hold one argument for each char specifier in 'fmt'. */
2618  argv_size = strlen(fmt)+1; /* +1 because of the command name. */
2619  argv = zrealloc(argv,sizeof(robj*)*argv_size);
2620 
2621  /* Build the arguments vector based on the format specifier. */
2622  argv[0] = createStringObject(cmdname,strlen(cmdname));
2623  argc++;
2624 
2625  /* Create the client and dispatch the command. */
2626  const char *p = fmt;
2627  while(*p) {
2628  if (*p == 'c') {
2629  char *cstr = va_arg(ap,char*);
2630  argv[argc++] = createStringObject(cstr,strlen(cstr));
2631  } else if (*p == 's') {
2632  robj *obj = va_arg(ap,void*);
2633  argv[argc++] = obj;
2634  incrRefCount(obj);
2635  } else if (*p == 'b') {
2636  char *buf = va_arg(ap,char*);
2637  size_t len = va_arg(ap,size_t);
2638  argv[argc++] = createStringObject(buf,len);
2639  } else if (*p == 'l') {
2640  long ll = va_arg(ap,long long);
2641  argv[argc++] = createObject(OBJ_STRING,sdsfromlonglong(ll));
2642  } else if (*p == 'v') {
2643  /* A vector of strings */
2644  robj **v = va_arg(ap, void*);
2645  size_t vlen = va_arg(ap, size_t);
2646 
2647  /* We need to grow argv to hold the vector's elements.
2648  * We resize by vector_len-1 elements, because we held
2649  * one element in argv for the vector already */
2650  argv_size += vlen-1;
2651  argv = zrealloc(argv,sizeof(robj*)*argv_size);
2652 
2653  size_t i = 0;
2654  for (i = 0; i < vlen; i++) {
2655  incrRefCount(v[i]);
2656  argv[argc++] = v[i];
2657  }
2658  } else if (*p == '!') {
2659  if (flags) (*flags) |= REDISMODULE_ARGV_REPLICATE;
2660  } else {
2661  goto fmterr;
2662  }
2663  p++;
2664  }
2665  *argcp = argc;
2666  return argv;
2667 
2668 fmterr:
2669  for (j = 0; j < argc; j++)
2670  decrRefCount(argv[j]);
2671  zfree(argv);
2672  return NULL;
2673 }
