2675 /* Exported API to call any Redis command from modules.
2676  * On success a RedisModuleCallReply object is returned, otherwise
2677  * NULL is returned and errno is set to the following values:
2678  *
2679  * EINVAL: command non existing, wrong arity, wrong format specifier.
2680  * EPERM: operation in Cluster instance with key in non local slot. */
2681 RedisModuleCallReply *RM_Call(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *cmdname, const char *fmt, ...) {
2682  struct redisCommand *cmd;
2683  client *c = NULL;
2684  robj **argv = NULL;
2685  int argc = 0, flags = 0;
2686  va_list ap;
2687  RedisModuleCallReply *reply = NULL;
2688  int replicate = 0; /* Replicate this command? */
2689 
2690  cmd = lookupCommandByCString((char*)cmdname);
2691  if (!cmd) {
2692  errno = EINVAL;
2693  return NULL;
2694  }
2695 
2696  /* Create the client and dispatch the command. */
2697  va_start(ap, fmt);
2698  c = createClient(-1);
2699  argv = moduleCreateArgvFromUserFormat(cmdname,fmt,&argc,&flags,ap);
2700  replicate = flags & REDISMODULE_ARGV_REPLICATE;
2701  va_end(ap);
2702 
2703  /* Setup our fake client for command execution. */
2704  c->flags |= CLIENT_MODULE;
2705  c->db = ctx->client->db;
2706  c->argv = argv;
2707  c->argc = argc;
2708  c->cmd = c->lastcmd = cmd;
2709  /* We handle the above format error only when the client is setup so that
2710  * we can free it normally. */
2711  if (argv == NULL) goto cleanup;
2712 
2713  /* Basic arity checks. */
2714  if ((cmd->arity > 0 && cmd->arity != argc) || (argc < -cmd->arity)) {
2715  errno = EINVAL;
2716  goto cleanup;
2717  }
2718 
2719  /* If this is a Redis Cluster node, we need to make sure the module is not
2720  * trying to access non-local keys, with the exception of commands
2721  * received from our master. */
2722  if (server.cluster_enabled && !(ctx->client->flags & CLIENT_MASTER)) {
2723  /* Duplicate relevant flags in the module client. */
2724  c->flags &= ~(CLIENT_READONLY|CLIENT_ASKING);
2725  c->flags |= ctx->client->flags & (CLIENT_READONLY|CLIENT_ASKING);
2726  if (getNodeByQuery(c,c->cmd,c->argv,c->argc,NULL,NULL) !=
2727  server.cluster->myself)
2728  {
2729  errno = EPERM;
2730  goto cleanup;
2731  }
2732  }
2733 
2734  /* If we are using single commands replication, we need to wrap what
2735  * we propagate into a MULTI/EXEC block, so that it will be atomic like
2736  * a Lua script in the context of AOF and slaves. */
2737  if (replicate) moduleReplicateMultiIfNeeded(ctx);
2738 
2739  /* Run the command */
2740  int call_flags = CMD_CALL_SLOWLOG | CMD_CALL_STATS;
2741  if (replicate) {
2742  call_flags |= CMD_CALL_PROPAGATE_AOF;
2743  call_flags |= CMD_CALL_PROPAGATE_REPL;
2744  }
2745  call(c,call_flags);
2746 
2747  /* Convert the result of the Redis command into a suitable Lua type.
2748  * The first thing we need is to create a single string from the client
2749  * output buffers. */
2750  sds proto = sdsnewlen(c->buf,c->bufpos);
2751  c->bufpos = 0;
2752  while(listLength(c->reply)) {
2753  clientReplyBlock *o = listNodeValue(listFirst(c->reply));
2754 
2755  proto = sdscatlen(proto,o->buf,o->used);
2756  listDelNode(c->reply,listFirst(c->reply));
2757  }
2758  reply = moduleCreateCallReplyFromProto(ctx,proto);
2759  autoMemoryAdd(ctx,REDISMODULE_AM_REPLY,reply);
2760 
2761 cleanup:
2762  freeClient(c);
2763  return reply;
2764 }

2768 const char *RM_CallReplyProto(RedisModuleCallReply *reply, size_t *len) {
2769  if (reply->proto) *len = sdslen(reply->proto);

2773 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
2774  * Modules data types
2775  *
2776  * When String DMA or using existing data structures is not enough, it is
2777  * possible to create new data types from scratch and export them to
2778  * Redis. The module must provide a set of callbacks for handling the
2779  * new values exported (for example in order to provide RDB saving/loading,
2780  * AOF rewrite, and so forth). In this section we define this API.
2781  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
2782 
2783 /* Turn a 9 chars name in the specified charset and a 10 bit encver into
2784  * a single 64 bit unsigned integer that represents this exact module name
2785  * and version. This final number is called a "type ID" and is used when
2786  * writing module exported values to RDB files, in order to re-associate the
2787  * value to the right module to load them during RDB loading.
2788  *
2789  * If the string is not of the right length or the charset is wrong, or
2790  * if encver is outside the unsigned 10 bit integer range, 0 is returned,
2791  * otherwise the function returns the right type ID.
2792  *
2793  * The resulting 64 bit integer is composed as follows:
2794  *
2795  * (high order bits) 6|6|6|6|6|6|6|6|6|10 (low order bits)
2796  *
2797  * The first 6 bits value is the first character, name[0], while the last
2798  * 6 bits value, immediately before the 10 bits integer, is name[8].
2799  * The last 10 bits are the encoding version.
2800  *
2801  * Note that a name and encver combo of "AAAAAAAAA" and 0, will produce
2802  * zero as return value, that is the same we use to signal errors, thus
2803  * this combination is invalid, and also useless since type names should
2804  * try to be vary to avoid collisions. */
2805 
2806 const char *ModuleTypeNameCharSet =
2807  "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ"
2808  "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz"
2809  "0123456789-_";
2810 
2811 uint64_t moduleTypeEncodeId(const char *name, int encver) {
2812  /* We use 64 symbols so that we can map each character into 6 bits
2813  * of the final output. */
2814  const char *cset = ModuleTypeNameCharSet;
2815  if (strlen(name) != 9) return 0;
2816  if (encver < 0 || encver > 1023) return 0;
2817 
2818  uint64_t id = 0;
2819  for (int j = 0; j < 9; j++) {
2820  char *p = strchr(cset,name[j]);
2821  if (!p) return 0;
2822  unsigned long pos = p-cset;
2823  id = (id << 6) | pos;
2824  }
2825  id = (id << 10) | encver;
2826  return id;
2827 }
2828 
2829 /* Search, in the list of exported data types of all the modules registered,
2830  * a type with the same name as the one given. Returns the moduleType
2831  * structure pointer if such a module is found, or NULL otherwise. */
2832 moduleType *moduleTypeLookupModuleByName(const char *name) {
2833  dictIterator *di = dictGetIterator(modules);
2834  dictEntry *de;
2835 
2836  while ((de = dictNext(di)) != NULL) {
2837  struct RedisModule *module = dictGetVal(de);
2838  listIter li;
2839  listNode *ln;
2840 
2841  listRewind(module->types,&li);
2842  while((ln = listNext(&li))) {
2843  moduleType *mt = ln->value;
2844  if (memcmp(name,mt->name,sizeof(mt->name)) == 0) {
2845  dictReleaseIterator(di);
2846  return mt;
2847  }
2848  }
2849  }
2850  dictReleaseIterator(di);
2851  return NULL;
2852 }
2853 
2854 /* Lookup a module by ID, with caching. This function is used during RDB
2855  * loading. Modules exporting data types should never be able to unload, so
2856  * our cache does not need to expire. */
2857 #define MODULE_LOOKUP_CACHE_SIZE 3
2858 
2859 moduleType *moduleTypeLookupModuleByID(uint64_t id) {
2860  static struct {
2861  uint64_t id;
2862  moduleType *mt;
2863  } cache[MODULE_LOOKUP_CACHE_SIZE];
2864 
2865  /* Search in cache to start. */
2866  int j;
2867  for (j = 0; j < MODULE_LOOKUP_CACHE_SIZE && cache[j].mt != NULL; j++)
2868  if (cache[j].id == id) return cache[j].mt;
2869 
2870  /* Slow module by module lookup. */
2871  moduleType *mt = NULL;
2872  dictIterator *di = dictGetIterator(modules);
2873  dictEntry *de;
2874 
2875  while ((de = dictNext(di)) != NULL && mt == NULL) {
2876  struct RedisModule *module = dictGetVal(de);
2877  listIter li;
2878  listNode *ln;
2879 
2880  listRewind(module->types,&li);
2881  while((ln = listNext(&li))) {
2882  moduleType *this_mt = ln->value;
2883  /* Compare only the 54 bit module identifier and not the
2884  * encoding version. */
2885  if (this_mt->id >> 10 == id >> 10) {
2886  mt = this_mt;
2887  break;
2888  }
2889  }
2890  }
2891  dictReleaseIterator(di);
2892 
2893  /* Add to cache if possible. */
2894  if (mt && j < MODULE_LOOKUP_CACHE_SIZE) {
2895  cache[j].id = id;
2896  cache[j].mt = mt;
2897  }
2898  return mt;
2899 }

2901 /* Turn an (unresolved) module ID into a type name, to show the user an
2902  * error when RDB files contain module data we can't load.
2903  * The buffer pointed by 'name' must be 10 bytes at least. The function will
2904  * fill it with a null terminated module name. */
2905 void moduleTypeNameByID(char *name, uint64_t moduleid) {
2906  const char *cset = ModuleTypeNameCharSet;
2907 
2908  name[9] = '\0';
2909  char *p = name+8;
2910  moduleid >>= 10;
2911  for (int j = 0; j < 9; j++) {
2912  *p-- = cset[moduleid & 63];
2913  moduleid >>= 6;
2914  }
2915 }
2916 
2917 /* Register a new data type exported by the module. The parameters are the
2918  * following. Please for in depth documentation check the modules API
2919  * documentation, especially the TYPES.md file.
2920  *
2921  * * **name**: A 9 characters data type name that MUST be unique in the Redis
2922  * Modules ecosystem. Be creative... and there will be no collisions. Use
2923  * the charset A-Z a-z 9-0, plus the two "-_" characters. A good
2924  * idea is to use, for example `<typename>-<vendor>`. For example
2925  * "tree-AntZ" may mean "Tree data structure by @antirez". To use both
2926  * lower case and upper case letters helps in order to prevent collisions.
2927  * * **encver**: Encoding version, which is, the version of the serialization
2928  * that a module used in order to persist data. As long as the "name"
2929  * matches, the RDB loading will be dispatched to the type callbacks
2930  * whatever 'encver' is used, however the module can understand if
2931  * the encoding it must load are of an older version of the module.
2932  * For example the module "tree-AntZ" initially used encver=0. Later
2933  * after an upgrade, it started to serialize data in a different format
2934  * and to register the type with encver=1. However this module may
2935  * still load old data produced by an older version if the rdb_load
2936  * callback is able to check the encver value and act accordingly.
2937  * The encver must be a positive value between 0 and 1023.
2938  * * **typemethods_ptr** is a pointer to a RedisModuleTypeMethods structure
2939  * that should be populated with the methods callbacks and structure
2940  * version, like in the following example:
2941  *
2942  * RedisModuleTypeMethods tm = {
2943  * .version = REDISMODULE_TYPE_METHOD_VERSION,
2944  * .rdb_load = myType_RDBLoadCallBack,
2945  * .rdb_save = myType_RDBSaveCallBack,
2946  * .aof_rewrite = myType_AOFRewriteCallBack,
2947  * .free = myType_FreeCallBack,
2948  *
2949  * // Optional fields
2950  * .digest = myType_DigestCallBack,
2951  * .mem_usage = myType_MemUsageCallBack,
2952  * }
2953  *
2954  * * **rdb_load**: A callback function pointer that loads data from RDB files.
2955  * * **rdb_save**: A callback function pointer that saves data to RDB files.
2956  * * **aof_rewrite**: A callback function pointer that rewrites data as commands.
2957  * * **digest**: A callback function pointer that is used for `DEBUG DIGEST`.
2958  * * **free**: A callback function pointer that can free a type value.
2959  *
2960  * The **digest* and **mem_usage** methods should currently be omitted since
2961  * they are not yet implemented inside the Redis modules core.
2962  *
2963  * Note: the module name "AAAAAAAAA" is reserved and produces an error, it
2964  * happens to be pretty lame as well.
2965  *
2966  * If there is already a module registering a type with the same name,
2967  * and if the module name or encver is invalid, NULL is returned.
2968  * Otherwise the new type is registered into Redis, and a reference of
2969  * type RedisModuleType is returned: the caller of the function should store
2970  * this reference into a gobal variable to make future use of it in the
2971  * modules type API, since a single module may register multiple types.
2972  * Example code fragment:
2973  *
2974  * static RedisModuleType *BalancedTreeType;
2975  *
2976  * int RedisModule_OnLoad(RedisModuleCtx *ctx) {
2977  * // some code here ...
2978  * BalancedTreeType = RM_CreateDataType(...);
2979  * }
2980  */
2981 moduleType *RM_CreateDataType(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *name, int encver, void *typemethods_ptr) {
2982  uint64_t id = moduleTypeEncodeId(name,encver);
2983  if (id == 0) return NULL;
2984  if (moduleTypeLookupModuleByName(name) != NULL) return NULL;
2985 
2986  long typemethods_version = ((long*)typemethods_ptr)[0];
2987  if (typemethods_version == 0) return NULL;
2988 
2989  struct typemethods {
2990  uint64_t version;
2991  moduleTypeLoadFunc rdb_load;
2992  moduleTypeSaveFunc rdb_save;
2993  moduleTypeRewriteFunc aof_rewrite;
2994  moduleTypeMemUsageFunc mem_usage;
2995  moduleTypeDigestFunc digest;
2996  moduleTypeFreeFunc free;
2997  } *tms = (struct typemethods*) typemethods_ptr;
2998 
2999  moduleType *mt = zcalloc(sizeof(*mt));
3000  mt->id = id;
3001  mt->module = ctx->module;
3002  mt->rdb_load = tms->rdb_load;
3003  mt->rdb_save = tms->rdb_save;
3004  mt->aof_rewrite = tms->aof_rewrite;
3005  mt->mem_usage = tms->mem_usage;
3006  mt->digest = tms->digest;
3007  mt->free = tms->free;
3008  memcpy(mt->name,name,sizeof(mt->name));
3009  listAddNodeTail(ctx->module->types,mt);
3010  return mt;
3011 }

3278 /* Add a new element to the digest. This function can be called multiple times
3279  * one element after the other, for all the elements that constitute a given
3280  * data structure. The function call must be followed by the call to
3281  * `RedisModule_DigestEndSequence` eventually, when all the elements that are
3282  * always in a given order are added. See the Redis Modules data types
3283  * documentation for more info. However this is a quick example that uses Redis
3284  * data types as an example.
3285  *
3286  * To add a sequence of unordered elements (for example in the case of a Redis
3287  * Set), the pattern to use is:
3288  *
3289  * foreach element {
3290  * AddElement(element);
3291  * EndSequence();
3292  * }
3293  *
3294  * Because Sets are not ordered, so every element added has a position that
3295  * does not depend from the other. However if instead our elements are
3296  * ordered in pairs, like field-value pairs of an Hash, then one should
3297  * use:
3298  *
3299  * foreach key,value {
3300  * AddElement(key);
3301  * AddElement(value);
3302  * EndSquence();
3303  * }
3304  *
3305  * Because the key and value will be always in the above order, while instead
3306  * the single key-value pairs, can appear in any position into a Redis hash.
3307  *
3308  * A list of ordered elements would be implemented with:
3309  *
3310  * foreach element {
3311  * AddElement(element);
3312  * }
3313  * EndSequence();
3314  *
3315  */
3316 void RM_DigestAddStringBuffer(RedisModuleDigest *md, unsigned char *ele, size_t len) {
3317  mixDigest(md->o,ele,len);
3318 }

3336  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

3338 /* Emits a command into the AOF during the AOF rewriting process. This function
3339  * is only called in the context of the aof_rewrite method of data types exported
3340  * by a module. The command works exactly like RedisModule_Call() in the way
3341  * the parameters are passed, but it does not return anything as the error
3342  * handling is performed by Redis itself. */
3343 void RM_EmitAOF(RedisModuleIO *io, const char *cmdname, const char *fmt, ...) {
3344  if (io->error) return;
3345  struct redisCommand *cmd;
3346  robj **argv = NULL;
3347  int argc = 0, flags = 0, j;
3348  va_list ap;
3349 
3350  cmd = lookupCommandByCString((char*)cmdname);
3351  if (!cmd) {
3352  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
3353  "Fatal: AOF method for module data type '%s' tried to "
3354  "emit unknown command '%s'",
3355  io->type->name, cmdname);
3356  io->error = 1;
3357  errno = EINVAL;
3358  return;
3359  }
3360 
3361  /* Emit the arguments into the AOF in Redis protocol format. */
3362  va_start(ap, fmt);
3363  argv = moduleCreateArgvFromUserFormat(cmdname,fmt,&argc,&flags,ap);
3364  va_end(ap);
3365  if (argv == NULL) {
3366  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
3367  "Fatal: AOF method for module data type '%s' tried to "
3368  "call RedisModule_EmitAOF() with wrong format specifiers '%s'",
3369  io->type->name, fmt);
3370  io->error = 1;
3371  errno = EINVAL;
3372  return;
3373  }
3374 
3375  /* Bulk count. */
3376  if (!io->error && rioWriteBulkCount(io->rio,'*',argc) == 0)
3377  io->error = 1;
3378 
3379  /* Arguments. */
3380  for (j = 0; j < argc; j++) {
3381  if (!io->error && rioWriteBulkObject(io->rio,argv[j]) == 0)
3382  io->error = 1;
3383  decrRefCount(argv[j]);
3384  }
3385  zfree(argv);
3386  return;
3387 }

3479 /* This is called from blocked.c in order to unblock a client: may be called
3480  * for multiple reasons while the client is in the middle of being blocked
3481  * because the client is terminated, but is also called for cleanup when a
3482  * client is unblocked in a clean way after replaying.
3483  *
3484  * What we do here is just to set the client to NULL in the redis module
3485  * blocked client handle. This way if the client is terminated while there
3486  * is a pending threaded operation involving the blocked client, we'll know
3487  * that the client no longer exists and no reply callback should be called.
3488  *
3489  * The structure RedisModuleBlockedClient will be always deallocated when
3490  * running the list of clients blocked by a module that need to be unblocked. */
3491 void unblockClientFromModule(client *c) {
3492  RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc = c->bpop.module_blocked_handle;
3493 
3494  /* Call the disconnection callback if any. */
3495  if (bc->disconnect_callback) {
3496  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
3497  ctx.blocked_privdata = bc->privdata;
3498  ctx.module = bc->module;
3499  ctx.client = bc->client;
3500  bc->disconnect_callback(&ctx,bc);
3501  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
3502  }
3503 
3504  bc->client = NULL;
3505  /* Reset the client for a new query since, for blocking commands implemented
3506  * into modules, we do not it immediately after the command returns (and
3507  * the client blocks) in order to be still able to access the argument
3508  * vector from callbacks. */
3509  resetClient(c);
3510 }

3512 /* Block a client in the context of a blocking command, returning an handle
3513  * which will be used, later, in order to unblock the client with a call to
3514  * RedisModule_UnblockClient(). The arguments specify callback functions
3515  * and a timeout after which the client is unblocked.
3516  *
3517  * The callbacks are called in the following contexts:
3518  *
3519  * reply_callback: called after a successful RedisModule_UnblockClient()
3520  * call in order to reply to the client and unblock it.
3521  *
3522  * reply_timeout: called when the timeout is reached in order to send an
3523  * error to the client.
3524  *
3525  * free_privdata: called in order to free the private data that is passed
3526  * by RedisModule_UnblockClient() call.
3527  */
3528 RedisModuleBlockedClient *RM_BlockClient(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleCmdFunc reply_callback, RedisModuleCmdFunc timeout_callback, void (*free_privdata)(RedisModuleCtx*,void*), long long timeout_ms) {
3529  client *c = ctx->client;
3530  int islua = c->flags & CLIENT_LUA;
3531  int ismulti = c->flags & CLIENT_MULTI;
3532 
3533  c->bpop.module_blocked_handle = zmalloc(sizeof(RedisModuleBlockedClient));
3534  RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc = c->bpop.module_blocked_handle;
3535 
3536  /* We need to handle the invalid operation of calling modules blocking
3537  * commands from Lua or MULTI. We actually create an already aborted
3538  * (client set to NULL) blocked client handle, and actually reply with
3539  * an error. */
3540  bc->client = (islua || ismulti) ? NULL : c;
3541  bc->module = ctx->module;
3542  bc->reply_callback = reply_callback;
3543  bc->timeout_callback = timeout_callback;
3544  bc->disconnect_callback = NULL; /* Set by RM_SetDisconnectCallback() */
3545  bc->free_privdata = free_privdata;
3546  bc->privdata = NULL;
3547  bc->reply_client = createClient(-1);
3548  bc->reply_client->flags |= CLIENT_MODULE;
3549  bc->dbid = c->db->id;
3550  c->bpop.timeout = timeout_ms ? (mstime()+timeout_ms) : 0;
3551 
3552  if (islua || ismulti) {
3553  c->bpop.module_blocked_handle = NULL;
3554  addReplyError(c, islua ?
3555  "Blocking module command called from Lua script" :
3556  "Blocking module command called from transaction");
3557  } else {
3558  blockClient(c,BLOCKED_MODULE);
3559  }
3560  return bc;
3561 }

3563 /* Unblock a client blocked by `RedisModule_BlockedClient`. This will trigger
3564  * the reply callbacks to be called in order to reply to the client.
3565  * The 'privdata' argument will be accessible by the reply callback, so
3566  * the caller of this function can pass any value that is needed in order to
3567  * actually reply to the client.
3568  *
3569  * A common usage for 'privdata' is a thread that computes something that
3570  * needs to be passed to the client, included but not limited some slow
3571  * to compute reply or some reply obtained via networking.
3572  *
3573  * Note: this function can be called from threads spawned by the module. */
3574 int RM_UnblockClient(RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc, void *privdata) {
3575  pthread_mutex_lock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3576  bc->privdata = privdata;
3577  listAddNodeTail(moduleUnblockedClients,bc);
3578  if (write(server.module_blocked_pipe[1],"A",1) != 1) {
3579  /* Ignore the error, this is best-effort. */
3580  }
3581  pthread_mutex_unlock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3582  return REDISMODULE_OK;
3583 }

3587 int RM_AbortBlock(RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc) {

3589  bc->disconnect_callback = NULL;

3593 /* Set a callback that will be called if a blocked client disconnects
3594  * before the module has a chance to call RedisModule_UnblockClient()
3595  *
3596  * Usually what you want to do there, is to cleanup your module state
3597  * so that you can call RedisModule_UnblockClient() safely, otherwise
3598  * the client will remain blocked forever if the timeout is large.
3599  *
3600  * Notes:
3601  *
3602  * 1. It is not safe to call Reply* family functions here, it is also
3603  * useless since the client is gone.
3604  *
3605  * 2. This callback is not called if the client disconnects because of
3606  * a timeout. In such a case, the client is unblocked automatically
3607  * and the timeout callback is called.
3608  */
3609 void RM_SetDisconnectCallback(RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc, RedisModuleDisconnectFunc callback) {
3610  bc->disconnect_callback = callback;
3611 }

3613 /* This function will check the moduleUnblockedClients queue in order to
3614  * call the reply callback and really unblock the client.
3615  *
3616  * Clients end into this list because of calls to RM_UnblockClient(),
3617  * however it is possible that while the module was doing work for the
3618  * blocked client, it was terminated by Redis (for timeout or other reasons).
3619  * When this happens the RedisModuleBlockedClient structure in the queue
3620  * will have the 'client' field set to NULL. */
3621 void moduleHandleBlockedClients(void) {
3622  listNode *ln;
3623  RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc;
3624 
3625  pthread_mutex_lock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3626  /* Here we unblock all the pending clients blocked in modules operations
3627  * so we can read every pending "awake byte" in the pipe. */
3628  char buf[1];
3629  while (read(server.module_blocked_pipe[0],buf,1) == 1);
3630  while (listLength(moduleUnblockedClients)) {
3631  ln = listFirst(moduleUnblockedClients);
3632  bc = ln->value;
3633  client *c = bc->client;
3634  listDelNode(moduleUnblockedClients,ln);
3635  pthread_mutex_unlock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3636 
3637  /* Release the lock during the loop, as long as we don't
3638  * touch the shared list. */
3639 
3640  /* Call the reply callback if the client is valid and we have
3641  * any callback. */
3642  if (c && bc->reply_callback) {
3643  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
3644  ctx.flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_BLOCKED_REPLY;
3645  ctx.blocked_privdata = bc->privdata;
3646  ctx.module = bc->module;
3647  ctx.client = bc->client;
3648  ctx.blocked_client = bc;
3649  bc->reply_callback(&ctx,(void**)c->argv,c->argc);
3650  moduleHandlePropagationAfterCommandCallback(&ctx);
3651  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
3652  }
3653 
3654  /* Free privdata if any. */
3655  if (bc->privdata && bc->free_privdata) {
3656  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
3657  if (c == NULL)
3658  ctx.flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_BLOCKED_DISCONNECTED;
3659  ctx.blocked_privdata = bc->privdata;
3660  ctx.module = bc->module;
3661  ctx.client = bc->client;
3662  bc->free_privdata(&ctx,bc->privdata);
3663  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
3664  }
3665 
3666  /* It is possible that this blocked client object accumulated
3667  * replies to send to the client in a thread safe context.
3668  * We need to glue such replies to the client output buffer and
3669  * free the temporary client we just used for the replies. */
3670  if (c) {
3671  if (bc->reply_client->bufpos)
3672  addReplyString(c,bc->reply_client->buf,
3673  bc->reply_client->bufpos);
3674  if (listLength(bc->reply_client->reply))
3675  listJoin(c->reply,bc->reply_client->reply);
3676  c->reply_bytes += bc->reply_client->reply_bytes;
3677  }
3678  freeClient(bc->reply_client);
3679 
3680  if (c != NULL) {
3681  /* Before unblocking the client, set the disconnect callback
3682  * to NULL, because if we reached this point, the client was
3683  * properly unblocked by the module. */
3684  bc->disconnect_callback = NULL;
3685  unblockClient(c);
3686  /* Put the client in the list of clients that need to write
3687  * if there are pending replies here. This is needed since
3688  * during a non blocking command the client may receive output. */
3689  if (clientHasPendingReplies(c) &&
3690  !(c->flags & CLIENT_PENDING_WRITE))
3691  {
3692  c->flags |= CLIENT_PENDING_WRITE;
3693  listAddNodeHead(server.clients_pending_write,c);
3694  }
3695  }
3696 
3697  /* Free 'bc' only after unblocking the client, since it is
3698  * referenced in the client blocking context, and must be valid
3699  * when calling unblockClient(). */
3700  zfree(bc);
3701 
3702  /* Lock again before to iterate the loop. */
3703  pthread_mutex_lock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3704  }
3705  pthread_mutex_unlock(&moduleUnblockedClientsMutex);
3706 }

3708 /* Called when our client timed out. After this function unblockClient()
3709  * is called, and it will invalidate the blocked client. So this function
3710  * does not need to do any cleanup. Eventually the module will call the
3711  * API to unblock the client and the memory will be released. */
3712 void moduleBlockedClientTimedOut(client *c) {
3713  RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc = c->bpop.module_blocked_handle;

3718  ctx.blocked_client = bc;

3722  * because the blocked client will be automatically disconnected in
3723  * this case, and the user can still hook using the timeout callback. */
3724  bc->disconnect_callback = NULL;
3725 }

3759 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
3760  * Thread Safe Contexts
3761  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
3762 
3763 /* Return a context which can be used inside threads to make Redis context
3764  * calls with certain modules APIs. If 'bc' is not NULL then the module will
3765  * be bound to a blocked client, and it will be possible to use the
3766  * `RedisModule_Reply*` family of functions to accumulate a reply for when the
3767  * client will be unblocked. Otherwise the thread safe context will be
3768  * detached by a specific client.
3769  *
3770  * To call non-reply APIs, the thread safe context must be prepared with:
3771  *
3772  * RedisModule_ThreadSafeCallStart(ctx);
3773  * ... make your call here ...
3774  * RedisModule_ThreadSafeCallStop(ctx);
3775  *
3776  * This is not needed when using `RedisModule_Reply*` functions, assuming
3777  * that a blocked client was used when the context was created, otherwise
3778  * no RedisModule_Reply* call should be made at all.
3779  *
3780  * TODO: thread safe contexts do not inherit the blocked client
3781  * selected database. */
3782 RedisModuleCtx *RM_GetThreadSafeContext(RedisModuleBlockedClient *bc) {
3783  RedisModuleCtx *ctx = zmalloc(sizeof(*ctx));
3784  RedisModuleCtx empty = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
3785  memcpy(ctx,&empty,sizeof(empty));
3786  if (bc) {
3787  ctx->blocked_client = bc;
3788  ctx->module = bc->module;
3789  }
3790  ctx->flags |= REDISMODULE_CTX_THREAD_SAFE;
3791  /* Even when the context is associated with a blocked client, we can't
3792  * access it safely from another thread, so we create a fake client here
3793  * in order to keep things like the currently selected database and similar
3794  * things. */
3795  ctx->client = createClient(-1);
3796  if (bc) selectDb(ctx->client,bc->dbid);
3797  return ctx;
3798 }

3829 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
3830  * Module Keyspace Notifications API
3831  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
3832 
3833 /* Subscribe to keyspace notifications. This is a low-level version of the
3834  * keyspace-notifications API. A module can register callbacks to be notified
3835  * when keyspce events occur.
3836  *
3837  * Notification events are filtered by their type (string events, set events,
3838  * etc), and the subscriber callback receives only events that match a specific
3839  * mask of event types.
3840  *
3841  * When subscribing to notifications with RedisModule_SubscribeToKeyspaceEvents
3842  * the module must provide an event type-mask, denoting the events the subscriber
3843  * is interested in. This can be an ORed mask of any of the following flags:
3844  *
3845  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_GENERIC: Generic commands like DEL, EXPIRE, RENAME
3846  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_STRING: String events
3847  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_LIST: List events
3848  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_SET: Set events
3849  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_HASH: Hash events
3850  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_ZSET: Sorted Set events
3851  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_EXPIRED: Expiration events
3852  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_EVICTED: Eviction events
3853  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_STREAM: Stream events
3854  * - REDISMODULE_NOTIFY_ALL: All events
3855  *
3856  * We do not distinguish between key events and keyspace events, and it is up
3857  * to the module to filter the actions taken based on the key.
3858  *
3859  * The subscriber signature is:
3860  *
3861  * int (*RedisModuleNotificationFunc) (RedisModuleCtx *ctx, int type,
3862  * const char *event,
3863  * RedisModuleString *key);
3864  *
3865  * `type` is the event type bit, that must match the mask given at registration
3866  * time. The event string is the actual command being executed, and key is the
3867  * relevant Redis key.
3868  *
3869  * Notification callback gets executed with a redis context that can not be
3870  * used to send anything to the client, and has the db number where the event
3871  * occurred as its selected db number.
3872  *
3873  * Notice that it is not necessary to enable notifications in redis.conf for
3874  * module notifications to work.
3875  *
3876  * Warning: the notification callbacks are performed in a synchronous manner,
3877  * so notification callbacks must to be fast, or they would slow Redis down.
3878  * If you need to take long actions, use threads to offload them.
3879  *
3880  * See https://redis.io/topics/notifications for more information.
3881  */
3882 int RM_SubscribeToKeyspaceEvents(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, int types, RedisModuleNotificationFunc callback) {
3883  RedisModuleKeyspaceSubscriber *sub = zmalloc(sizeof(*sub));
3884  sub->module = ctx->module;
3885  sub->event_mask = types;
3886  sub->notify_callback = callback;
3887  sub->active = 0;
3888 
3889  listAddNodeTail(moduleKeyspaceSubscribers, sub);
3890  return REDISMODULE_OK;
3891 }
3892 
3893 /* Dispatcher for keyspace notifications to module subscriber functions.
3894  * This gets called only if at least one module requested to be notified on
3895  * keyspace notifications */
3896 void moduleNotifyKeyspaceEvent(int type, const char *event, robj *key, int dbid) {
3897  /* Don't do anything if there aren't any subscribers */
3898  if (listLength(moduleKeyspaceSubscribers) == 0) return;
3899 
3900  listIter li;
3901  listNode *ln;
3902  listRewind(moduleKeyspaceSubscribers,&li);
3903 
3904  /* Remove irrelevant flags from the type mask */
3905  type &= ~(NOTIFY_KEYEVENT | NOTIFY_KEYSPACE);
3906 
3907  while((ln = listNext(&li))) {
3908  RedisModuleKeyspaceSubscriber *sub = ln->value;
3909  /* Only notify subscribers on events matching they registration,
3910  * and avoid subscribers triggering themselves */
3911  if ((sub->event_mask & type) && sub->active == 0) {
3912  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
3913  ctx.module = sub->module;
3914  ctx.client = moduleFreeContextReusedClient;
3915  selectDb(ctx.client, dbid);
3916 
3917  /* mark the handler as active to avoid reentrant loops.
3918  * If the subscriber performs an action triggering itself,
3919  * it will not be notified about it. */
3920  sub->active = 1;
3921  sub->notify_callback(&ctx, type, event, key);
3922  sub->active = 0;
3923  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
3924  }
3925  }
3926 }

3934  RedisModuleKeyspaceSubscriber *sub = ln->value;
3935  if (sub->module == module) {
3936  listDelNode(moduleKeyspaceSubscribers, ln);
3937  zfree(sub);
3938  }
3939  }

3987 /* Register a callback receiver for cluster messages of type 'type'. If there
3988  * was already a registered callback, this will replace the callback function
3989  * with the one provided, otherwise if the callback is set to NULL and there
3990  * is already a callback for this function, the callback is unregistered
3991  * (so this API call is also used in order to delete the receiver). */
3992 void RM_RegisterClusterMessageReceiver(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, uint8_t type, RedisModuleClusterMessageReceiver callback) {
3993  if (!server.cluster_enabled) return;
3994 
3995  uint64_t module_id = moduleTypeEncodeId(ctx->module->name,0);
3996  moduleClusterReceiver *r = clusterReceivers[type], *prev = NULL;
3997  while(r) {
3998  if (r->module_id == module_id) {
3999  /* Found! Set or delete. */
4000  if (callback) {
4001  r->callback = callback;
4002  } else {
4003  /* Delete the receiver entry if the user is setting
4004  * it to NULL. Just unlink the receiver node from the
4005  * linked list. */
4006  if (prev)
4007  prev->next = r->next;
4008  else
4009  clusterReceivers[type]->next = r->next;
4010  zfree(r);
4011  }
4012  return;
4013  }
4014  prev = r;
4015  r = r->next;
4016  }
4017 
4018  /* Not found, let's add it. */
4019  if (callback) {
4020  r = zmalloc(sizeof(*r));
4021  r->module_id = module_id;
4022  r->module = ctx->module;
4023  r->callback = callback;
4024  r->next = clusterReceivers[type];
4025  clusterReceivers[type] = r;
4026  }
4027 }

4045 /* Return an array of string pointers, each string pointer points to a cluster
4046  * node ID of exactly REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_SIZE bytes (without any null term).
4047  * The number of returned node IDs is stored into `*numnodes`.
4048  * However if this function is called by a module not running an a Redis
4049  * instance with Redis Cluster enabled, NULL is returned instead.
4050  *
4051  * The IDs returned can be used with RedisModule_GetClusterNodeInfo() in order
4052  * to get more information about single nodes.
4053  *
4054  * The array returned by this function must be freed using the function
4055  * RedisModule_FreeClusterNodesList().
4056  *
4057  * Example:
4058  *
4059  * size_t count, j;
4060  * char **ids = RedisModule_GetClusterNodesList(ctx,&count);
4061  * for (j = 0; j < count; j++) {
4062  * RedisModule_Log("notice","Node %.*s",
4063  * REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN,ids[j]);
4064  * }
4065  * RedisModule_FreeClusterNodesList(ids);

4067 char **RM_GetClusterNodesList(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, size_t *numnodes) {
4068  UNUSED(ctx);
4069 
4070  if (!server.cluster_enabled) return NULL;
4071  size_t count = dictSize(server.cluster->nodes);
4072  char **ids = zmalloc((count+1)*REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4073  dictIterator *di = dictGetIterator(server.cluster->nodes);
4074  dictEntry *de;
4075  int j = 0;
4076  while((de = dictNext(di)) != NULL) {
4077  clusterNode *node = dictGetVal(de);
4078  if (node->flags & (CLUSTER_NODE_NOADDR|CLUSTER_NODE_HANDSHAKE)) continue;
4079  ids[j] = zmalloc(REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4080  memcpy(ids[j],node->name,REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4081  j++;
4082  }
4083  *numnodes = j;
4084  ids[j] = NULL; /* Null term so that FreeClusterNodesList does not need
4085  * to also get the count argument. */
4086  dictReleaseIterator(di);
4087  return ids;
4088 }

4113 /* Populate the specified info for the node having as ID the specified 'id',
4114  * then returns REDISMODULE_OK. Otherwise if the node ID does not exist from
4115  * the POV of this local node, REDISMODULE_ERR is returned.
4116  *
4117  * The arguments ip, master_id, port and flags can be NULL in case we don't
4118  * need to populate back certain info. If an ip and master_id (only populated
4119  * if the instance is a slave) are specified, they point to buffers holding
4120  * at least REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN bytes. The strings written back as ip
4121  * and master_id are not null terminated.
4122  *
4123  * The list of flags reported is the following:
4124  *
4125  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_MYSELF This node
4126  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_MASTER The node is a master
4127  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_SLAVE The node is a replica
4128  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_PFAIL We see the node as failing
4129  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_FAIL The cluster agrees the node is failing
4130  * * REDISMODULE_NODE_NOFAILOVER The slave is configured to never failover
4131  */
4132 
4133 clusterNode *clusterLookupNode(const char *name); /* We need access to internals */
4134 
4135 int RM_GetClusterNodeInfo(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, const char *id, char *ip, char *master_id, int *port, int *flags) {
4136  UNUSED(ctx);
4137 
4138  clusterNode *node = clusterLookupNode(id);
4139  if (node->flags & (CLUSTER_NODE_NOADDR|CLUSTER_NODE_HANDSHAKE))
4140  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
4141 
4142  if (ip) memcpy(ip,node->name,REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4143 
4144  if (master_id) {
4145  /* If the information is not available, the function will set the
4146  * field to zero bytes, so that when the field can't be populated the
4147  * function kinda remains predictable. */
4148  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_MASTER && node->slaveof)
4149  memcpy(master_id,node->slaveof->name,REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4150  else
4151  memset(master_id,0,REDISMODULE_NODE_ID_LEN);
4152  }
4153  if (port) *port = node->port;
4154 
4155  /* As usually we have to remap flags for modules, in order to ensure
4156  * we can provide binary compatibility. */
4157  if (flags) {
4158  *flags = 0;
4159  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_MYSELF) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_MYSELF;
4160  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_MASTER) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_MASTER;
4161  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_SLAVE) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_SLAVE;
4162  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_PFAIL) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_PFAIL;
4163  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_FAIL) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_FAIL;
4164  if (node->flags & CLUSTER_NODE_NOFAILOVER) *flags |= REDISMODULE_NODE_NOFAILOVER;
4165  }
4166  return REDISMODULE_OK;
4167 }

4169 /* Set Redis Cluster flags in order to change the normal behavior of
4170  * Redis Cluster, especially with the goal of disabling certain functions.
4171  * This is useful for modules that use the Cluster API in order to create
4172  * a different distributed system, but still want to use the Redis Cluster
4173  * message bus. Flags that can be set:
4174  *
4175  * CLUSTER_MODULE_FLAG_NO_FAILOVER
4176  * CLUSTER_MODULE_FLAG_NO_REDIRECTION
4177  *
4178  * With the following effects:
4179  *
4180  * NO_FAILOVER: prevent Redis Cluster slaves to failover a failing master.
4181  * Also disables the replica migration feature.
4182  *
4183  * NO_REDIRECTION: Every node will accept any key, without trying to perform
4184  * partitioning according to the user Redis Cluster algorithm.

4186  * cluster, but without effects. */
4187 void RM_SetClusterFlags(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, uint64_t flags) {
4188  UNUSED(ctx);

4190  server.cluster_module_flags |= CLUSTER_MODULE_FLAG_NO_FAILOVER;
4191  if (flags & REDISMODULE_CLUSTER_FLAG_NO_REDIRECTION)
4192  server.cluster_module_flags |= CLUSTER_MODULE_FLAG_NO_REDIRECTION;
4193 }

4195 /* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
4196  * Modules Timers API
4197  *
4198  * Module timers are an high precision "green timers" abstraction where
4199  * every module can register even millions of timers without problems, even if
4200  * the actual event loop will just have a single timer that is used to awake the
4201  * module timers subsystem in order to process the next event.
4202  *
4203  * All the timers are stored into a radix tree, ordered by expire time, when
4204  * the main Redis event loop timer callback is called, we try to process all
4205  * the timers already expired one after the other. Then we re-enter the event
4206  * loop registering a timer that will expire when the next to process module
4207  * timer will expire.
4208  *
4209  * Every time the list of active timers drops to zero, we unregister the
4210  * main event loop timer, so that there is no overhead when such feature is
4211  * not used.
4212  * -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
4213 
4214 static rax *Timers; /* The radix tree of all the timers sorted by expire. */
4215 long long aeTimer = -1; /* Main event loop (ae.c) timer identifier. */
4216 
4217 typedef void (*RedisModuleTimerProc)(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, void *data);
4218 
4219 /* The timer descriptor, stored as value in the radix tree. */
4220 typedef struct RedisModuleTimer {
4221  RedisModule *module; /* Module reference. */
4222  RedisModuleTimerProc callback; /* The callback to invoke on expire. */
4223  void *data; /* Private data for the callback. */
4224  int dbid; /* Database number selected by the original client. */
4225 } RedisModuleTimer;
4226 
4227 /* This is the timer handler that is called by the main event loop. We schedule
4228  * this timer to be called when the nearest of our module timers will expire. */
4229 int moduleTimerHandler(struct aeEventLoop *eventLoop, long long id, void *clientData) {
4230  UNUSED(eventLoop);
4231  UNUSED(id);
4232  UNUSED(clientData);
4233 
4234  /* To start let's try to fire all the timers already expired. */
4235  raxIterator ri;
4236  raxStart(&ri,Timers);
4237  uint64_t now = ustime();
4238  long long next_period = 0;
4239  while(1) {
4240  raxSeek(&ri,"^",NULL,0);
4241  if (!raxNext(&ri)) break;
4242  uint64_t expiretime;
4243  memcpy(&expiretime,ri.key,sizeof(expiretime));
4244  expiretime = ntohu64(expiretime);
4245  if (now >= expiretime) {
4246  RedisModuleTimer *timer = ri.data;
4247  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
4248 
4249  ctx.module = timer->module;
4250  ctx.client = moduleFreeContextReusedClient;
4251  selectDb(ctx.client, timer->dbid);
4252  timer->callback(&ctx,timer->data);
4253  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
4254  raxRemove(Timers,(unsigned char*)ri.key,ri.key_len,NULL);
4255  zfree(timer);
4256  } else {
4257  next_period = (expiretime-now)/1000; /* Scale to milliseconds. */
4258  break;
4259  }
4260  }
4261  raxStop(&ri);
4262 
4263  /* Reschedule the next timer or cancel it. */
4264  if (next_period <= 0) next_period = 1;
4265  return (raxSize(Timers) > 0) ? next_period : AE_NOMORE;
4266 }
4267 
4268 /* Create a new timer that will fire after `period` milliseconds, and will call
4269  * the specified function using `data` as argument. The returned timer ID can be
4270  * used to get information from the timer or to stop it before it fires. */
4271 RedisModuleTimerID RM_CreateTimer(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, mstime_t period, RedisModuleTimerProc callback, void *data) {
4272  RedisModuleTimer *timer = zmalloc(sizeof(*timer));
4273  timer->module = ctx->module;
4274  timer->callback = callback;
4275  timer->data = data;
4276  timer->dbid = ctx->client->db->id;
4277  uint64_t expiretime = ustime()+period*1000;
4278  uint64_t key;
4279 
4280  while(1) {
4281  key = htonu64(expiretime);
4282  if (raxFind(Timers, (unsigned char*)&key,sizeof(key)) == raxNotFound) {
4283  raxInsert(Timers,(unsigned char*)&key,sizeof(key),timer,NULL);
4284  break;
4285  } else {
4286  expiretime++;
4287  }
4288  }
4289 
4290  /* We need to install the main event loop timer if it's not already
4291  * installed, or we may need to refresh its period if we just installed
4292  * a timer that will expire sooner than any other else. */
4293  if (aeTimer != -1) {
4294  raxIterator ri;
4295  raxStart(&ri,Timers);
4296  raxSeek(&ri,"^",NULL,0);
4297  raxNext(&ri);
4298  if (memcmp(ri.key,&key,sizeof(key)) == 0) {
4299  /* This is the first key, we need to re-install the timer according
4300  * to the just added event. */
4301  aeDeleteTimeEvent(server.el,aeTimer);
4302  aeTimer = -1;
4303  }
4304  raxStop(&ri);
4305  }
4306 
4307  /* If we have no main timer (the old one was invalidated, or this is the
4308  * first module timer we have), install one. */
4309  if (aeTimer == -1)
4310  aeTimer = aeCreateTimeEvent(server.el,period,moduleTimerHandler,NULL,NULL);
4311 
4312  return key;
4313 }

4315 /* Stop a timer, returns REDISMODULE_OK if the timer was found, belonged to the

4317  * If not NULL, the data pointer is set to the value of the data argument when
4318  * the timer was created. */
4319 int RM_StopTimer(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleTimerID id, void **data) {

4321  if (timer == raxNotFound || timer->module != ctx->module)
4322  return REDISMODULE_ERR;

4324  raxRemove(Timers,(unsigned char*)&id,sizeof(id),NULL);
4325  zfree(timer);

4327 }

4449 /* Return an interator, setup in order to start iterating from the specified
4450  * key by applying the operator 'op', which is just a string specifying the
4451  * comparison operator to use in order to seek the first element. The
4452  * operators avalable are:
4453  *
4454  * "^" -- Seek the first (lexicographically smaller) key.
4455  * "$" -- Seek the last (lexicographically biffer) key.
4456  * ">" -- Seek the first element greter than the specified key.
4457  * ">=" -- Seek the first element greater or equal than the specified key.
4458  * "<" -- Seek the first element smaller than the specified key.
4459  * "<=" -- Seek the first element smaller or equal than the specified key.
4460  * "==" -- Seek the first element matching exactly the specified key.
4461  *
4462  * Note that for "^" and "$" the passed key is not used, and the user may
4463  * just pass NULL with a length of 0.
4464  *
4465  * If the element to start the iteration cannot be seeked based on the
4466  * key and operator passed, RedisModule_DictNext() / Prev() will just return
4467  * REDISMODULE_ERR at the first call, otherwise they'll produce elements.
4468  */
4469 RedisModuleDictIter *RM_DictIteratorStartC(RedisModuleDict *d, const char *op, void *key, size_t keylen) {
4470  RedisModuleDictIter *di = zmalloc(sizeof(*di));
4471  di->dict = d;
4472  raxStart(&di->ri,d->rax);
4473  raxSeek(&di->ri,op,key,keylen);
4474  return di;
4475 }

4480  return RM_DictIteratorStartC(d,op,key->ptr,sdslen(key->ptr));

4507 /* Return the current item of the dictionary iterator 'di' and steps to the
4508  * next element. If the iterator already yield the last element and there
4509  * are no other elements to return, NULL is returned, otherwise a pointer
4510  * to a string representing the key is provided, and the '*keylen' length
4511  * is set by reference (if keylen is not NULL). The '*dataptr', if not NULL
4512  * is set to the value of the pointer stored at the returned key as auxiliary
4513  * data (as set by the RedisModule_DictSet API).
4514  *
4515  * Usage example:
4516  *
4517  * ... create the iterator here ...
4518  * char *key;
4519  * void *data;
4520  * while((key = RedisModule_DictNextC(iter,&keylen,&data)) != NULL) {
4521  * printf("%.*s %p\n", (int)keylen, key, data);
4522  * }
4523  *
4524  * The returned pointer is of type void because sometimes it makes sense
4525  * to cast it to a char* sometimes to an unsigned char* depending on the
4526  * fact it contains or not binary data, so this API ends being more
4527  * comfortable to use.
4528  *
4529  * The validity of the returned pointer is until the next call to the
4530  * next/prev iterator step. Also the pointer is no longer valid once the
4531  * iterator is released. */
4532 void *RM_DictNextC(RedisModuleDictIter *di, size_t *keylen, void **dataptr) {
4533  if (!raxNext(&di->ri)) return NULL;
4534  if (keylen) *keylen = di->ri.key_len;
4535  if (dataptr) *dataptr = di->ri.data;
4536  return di->ri.key;
4537 }
4538 
4539 /* This function is exactly like RedisModule_DictNext() but after returning
4540  * the currently selected element in the iterator, it selects the previous
4541  * element (laxicographically smaller) instead of the next one. */
4542 void *RM_DictPrevC(RedisModuleDictIter *di, size_t *keylen, void **dataptr) {
4543  if (!raxPrev(&di->ri)) return NULL;
4544  if (keylen) *keylen = di->ri.key_len;
4545  if (dataptr) *dataptr = di->ri.data;
4546  return di->ri.key;
4547 }
4548 
4549 /* Like RedisModuleNextC(), but instead of returning an internally allocated
4550  * buffer and key length, it returns directly a module string object allocated
4551  * in the specified context 'ctx' (that may be NULL exactly like for the main
4552  * API RedisModule_CreateString).
4553  *
4554  * The returned string object should be deallocated after use, either manually
4555  * or by using a context that has automatic memory management active. */
4556 RedisModuleString *RM_DictNext(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleDictIter *di, void **dataptr) {
4557  size_t keylen;
4558  void *key = RM_DictNextC(di,&keylen,dataptr);
4559  if (key == NULL) return NULL;
4560  return RM_CreateString(ctx,key,keylen);
4561 }

4563 /* Like RedisModule_DictNext() but after returning the currently selected
4564  * element in the iterator, it selects the previous element (laxicographically
4565  * smaller) instead of the next one. */
4566 RedisModuleString *RM_DictPrev(RedisModuleCtx *ctx, RedisModuleDictIter *di, void **dataptr) {
4567  size_t keylen;
4568  void *key = RM_DictPrevC(di,&keylen,dataptr);
4569  if (key == NULL) return NULL;
4570  return RM_CreateString(ctx,key,keylen);
4571 }

4573 /* Compare the element currently pointed by the iterator to the specified
4574  * element given by key/keylen, according to the operator 'op' (the set of
4575  * valid operators are the same valid for RedisModule_DictIteratorStart).
4576  * If the comparision is successful the command returns REDISMODULE_OK
4577  * otherwise REDISMODULE_ERR is returned.
4578  *
4579  * This is useful when we want to just emit a lexicographical range, so
4580  * in the loop, as we iterate elements, we can also check if we are still
4581  * on range.
4582  *
4583  * The function returne REDISMODULE_ERR if the iterator reached the
4584  * end of elements condition as well. */
4585 int RM_DictCompareC(RedisModuleDictIter *di, const char *op, void *key, size_t keylen) {
4586  if (raxEOF(&di->ri)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
4587  int res = raxCompare(&di->ri,op,key,keylen);
4588  return res ? REDISMODULE_OK : REDISMODULE_ERR;
4589 }

4594  if (raxEOF(&di->ri)) return REDISMODULE_ERR;
4595  int res = raxCompare(&di->ri,op,key->ptr,sdslen(key->ptr));
4596  return res ? REDISMODULE_OK : REDISMODULE_ERR;
4597 }

4683 /* Load all the modules in the server.loadmodule_queue list, which is
4684  * populated by `loadmodule` directives in the configuration file.
4685  * We can't load modules directly when processing the configuration file
4686  * because the server must be fully initialized before loading modules.
4687  *
4688  * The function aborts the server on errors, since to start with missing
4689  * modules is not considered sane: clients may rely on the existence of
4690  * given commands, loading AOF also may need some modules to exist, and
4691  * if this instance is a slave, it must understand commands from master. */
4692 void moduleLoadFromQueue(void) {
4693  listIter li;
4694  listNode *ln;
4695 
4696  listRewind(server.loadmodule_queue,&li);
4697  while((ln = listNext(&li))) {
4698  struct moduleLoadQueueEntry *loadmod = ln->value;
4699  if (moduleLoad(loadmod->path,(void **)loadmod->argv,loadmod->argc)
4700  == C_ERR)
4701  {
4702  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
4703  "Can't load module from %s: server aborting",
4704  loadmod->path);
4705  exit(1);
4706  }
4707  }
4708 }

4716 void moduleUnregisterCommands(struct RedisModule *module) {
4717  /* Unregister all the commands registered by this module. */
4718  dictIterator *di = dictGetSafeIterator(server.commands);
4719  dictEntry *de;
4720  while ((de = dictNext(di)) != NULL) {
4721  struct redisCommand *cmd = dictGetVal(de);
4722  if (cmd->proc == RedisModuleCommandDispatcher) {
4723  RedisModuleCommandProxy *cp =
4724  (void*)(unsigned long)cmd->getkeys_proc;
4725  sds cmdname = cp->rediscmd->name;
4726  if (cp->module == module) {
4727  dictDelete(server.commands,cmdname);
4728  dictDelete(server.orig_commands,cmdname);
4729  sdsfree(cmdname);
4730  zfree(cp->rediscmd);
4731  zfree(cp);
4732  }
4733  }
4734  }
4735  dictReleaseIterator(di);
4736 }

4738 /* Load a module and initialize it. On success C_OK is returned, otherwise
4739  * C_ERR is returned. */
4740 int moduleLoad(const char *path, void **module_argv, int module_argc) {
4741  int (*onload)(void *, void **, int);
4742  void *handle;
4743  RedisModuleCtx ctx = REDISMODULE_CTX_INIT;
4744 
4745  handle = dlopen(path,RTLD_NOW|RTLD_LOCAL);
4746  if (handle == NULL) {
4747  serverLog(LL_WARNING, "Module %s failed to load: %s", path, dlerror());
4748  return C_ERR;
4749  }
4750  onload = (int (*)(void *, void **, int))(unsigned long) dlsym(handle,"RedisModule_OnLoad");
4751  if (onload == NULL) {
4752  dlclose(handle);
4753  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
4754  "Module %s does not export RedisModule_OnLoad() "
4755  "symbol. Module not loaded.",path);
4756  return C_ERR;
4757  }
4758  if (onload((void*)&ctx,module_argv,module_argc) == REDISMODULE_ERR) {
4759  if (ctx.module) {
4760  moduleUnregisterCommands(ctx.module);
4761  moduleFreeModuleStructure(ctx.module);
4762  }
4763  dlclose(handle);
4764  serverLog(LL_WARNING,
4765  "Module %s initialization failed. Module not loaded",path);
4766  return C_ERR;
4767  }
4768 
4769  /* Redis module loaded! Register it. */
4770  dictAdd(modules,ctx.module->name,ctx.module);
4771  ctx.module->handle = handle;
4772  serverLog(LL_NOTICE,"Module '%s' loaded from %s",ctx.module->name,path);
4773  moduleFreeContext(&ctx);
4774  return C_OK;
4775 }
4776 
4777 
4778 /* Unload the module registered with the specified name. On success
4779  * C_OK is returned, otherwise C_ERR is returned and errno is set
4780  * to the following values depending on the type of error:
4781  *
4782  * * ENONET: No such module having the specified name.
4783  * * EBUSY: The module exports a new data type and can only be reloaded. */
4784 int moduleUnload(sds name) {
4785  struct RedisModule *module = dictFetchValue(modules,name);
4786 
4787  if (module == NULL) {
4788  errno = ENOENT;
4789  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
4790  }
4791 
4792  if (listLength(module->types)) {
4793  errno = EBUSY;
4794  return REDISMODULE_ERR;
4795  }
4796 
4797  moduleUnregisterCommands(module);
4798 
4799  /* Remove any notification subscribers this module might have */
4800  moduleUnsubscribeNotifications(module);
4801 
4802  /* Unregister all the hooks. TODO: Yet no hooks support here. */
4803 
4804  /* Unload the dynamic library. */
4805  if (dlclose(module->handle) == -1) {
4806  char *error = dlerror();
4807  if (error == NULL) error = "Unknown error";
4808  serverLog(LL_WARNING,"Error when trying to close the %s module: %s",
4809  module->name, error);
4810  }
4811 
4812  /* Remove from list of modules. */
4813  serverLog(LL_NOTICE,"Module %s unloaded",module->name);
4814  dictDelete(modules,module->name);
4815  module->name = NULL; /* The name was already freed by dictDelete(). */
4816  moduleFreeModuleStructure(module);
4817 
4818  return REDISMODULE_OK;
4819 }

4821 /* Redis MODULE command.
4822  *
4823  * MODULE LOAD <path> [args...] */
4824 void moduleCommand(client *c) {
4825  char *subcmd = c->argv[1]->ptr;
4826  if (c->argc == 2 && !strcasecmp(subcmd,"help")) {
4827  const char *help[] = {
4828 "LIST -- Return a list of loaded modules.",
4829 "LOAD <path> [arg ...] -- Load a module library from <path>.",
4830 "UNLOAD <name> -- Unload a module.",
4831 NULL
4832  };
4833  addReplyHelp(c, help);
4834  } else
4835  if (!strcasecmp(subcmd,"load") && c->argc >= 3) {
4836  robj **argv = NULL;
4837  int argc = 0;
4838 
4839  if (c->argc > 3) {
4840  argc = c->argc - 3;
4841  argv = &c->argv[3];
4842  }
4843 
4844  if (moduleLoad(c->argv[2]->ptr,(void **)argv,argc) == C_OK)
4845  addReply(c,shared.ok);
4846  else
4847  addReplyError(c,
4848  "Error loading the extension. Please check the server logs.");
4849  } else if (!strcasecmp(subcmd,"unload") && c->argc == 3) {
4850  if (moduleUnload(c->argv[2]->ptr) == C_OK)
4851  addReply(c,shared.ok);
4852  else {
4853  char *errmsg;
4854  switch(errno) {
4855  case ENOENT:
4856  errmsg = "no such module with that name";
4857  break;
4858  case EBUSY:
4859  errmsg = "the module exports one or more module-side data types, can't unload";
4860  break;
4861  default:
4862  errmsg = "operation not possible.";
4863  break;
4864  }
4865  addReplyErrorFormat(c,"Error unloading module: %s",errmsg);
4866  }
4867  } else if (!strcasecmp(subcmd,"list") && c->argc == 2) {
4868  dictIterator *di = dictGetIterator(modules);
4869  dictEntry *de;
4870 
4871  addReplyMultiBulkLen(c,dictSize(modules));
4872  while ((de = dictNext(di)) != NULL) {
4873  sds name = dictGetKey(de);
4874  struct RedisModule *module = dictGetVal(de);
4875  addReplyMultiBulkLen(c,4);
4876  addReplyBulkCString(c,"name");
4877  addReplyBulkCBuffer(c,name,sdslen(name));
4878  addReplyBulkCString(c,"ver");
4879  addReplyLongLong(c,module->ver);
4880  }
4881  dictReleaseIterator(di);
4882  } else {
4883  addReplySubcommandSyntaxError(c);
4884  return;
4885  }
4886 }
